https://schema.org/3DModel.label: 3DModel
https://schema.org/3DModel.comment: A 3D model represents some kind of 3D content, which may have encodings in one or more MediaObjects. Many 3D formats are available (e.g. see Wikipedia); specific encoding formats can be represented using the encodingFormat property applied to the relevant MediaObject. For the case of a single file published after Zip compression, the convention of appending '+zip' to the encodingFormat can be used. Geospatial, AR/VR, artistic/animation, gaming, engineering and scientific content can all be represented using 3DModel.

https://schema.org/AMRadioChannel.label: AMRadioChannel
https://schema.org/AMRadioChannel.comment: A radio channel that uses AM.

https://schema.org/APIReference.label: APIReference
https://schema.org/APIReference.comment: Reference documentation for application programming interfaces (APIs).

https://schema.org/AcceptAction.label: AcceptAction
https://schema.org/AcceptAction.comment:
The act of committing to/adopting an object.

Related actions:

  • RejectAction: The antonym of AcceptAction.

https://schema.org/Accommodation.label: Accommodation
https://schema.org/Accommodation.comment:
An accommodation is a place that can accommodate human beings, e.g. a hotel room, a camping pitch, or a meeting room. Many accommodations are for overnight stays, but this is not a mandatory requirement. For more specific types of accommodations not defined in schema.org, one can use additionalType with external vocabularies.

See also the dedicated document on the use of schema.org for marking up hotels and other forms of accommodations.

https://schema.org/AccountingService.label: AccountingService
https://schema.org/AccountingService.comment:
Accountancy business.

As a LocalBusiness it can be described as a provider of one or more Service(s).

https://schema.org/AchieveAction.label: AchieveAction
https://schema.org/AchieveAction.comment: The act of accomplishing something via previous efforts. It is an instantaneous action rather than an ongoing process.

https://schema.org/Action.label: Action
https://schema.org/Action.comment:
An action performed by a direct agent and indirect participants upon a direct object. Optionally happens at a location with the help of an inanimate instrument. The execution of the action may produce a result. Specific action sub-type documentation specifies the exact expectation of each argument/role.

See also blog post and Actions overview document.

https://schema.org/ActionAccessSpecifica.label: ActionAccessSpecification
https://schema.org/ActionAccessSpecifica.comment: A set of requirements that must be fulfilled in order to perform an Action.

https://schema.org/ActivateAction.label: ActivateAction
https://schema.org/ActivateAction.comment: The act of starting or activating a device or application (e.g. starting a timer or turning on a flashlight).

https://schema.org/ActivationFee.label: ActivationFee
https://schema.org/ActivationFee.comment: Represents the activation fee part of the total price for an offered product, for example a cellphone contract.

https://schema.org/ActiveActionStatus.label: ActiveActionStatus
https://schema.org/ActiveActionStatus.comment: An in-progress action (e.g., while watching the movie, or driving to a location).

https://schema.org/ActiveNotRecruiting.label: ActiveNotRecruiting
https://schema.org/ActiveNotRecruiting.comment: Active, but not recruiting new participants.

https://schema.org/AddAction.label: AddAction
https://schema.org/AddAction.comment: The act of editing by adding an object to a collection.

https://schema.org/AdministrativeArea.label: AdministrativeArea
https://schema.org/AdministrativeArea.comment: A geographical region, typically under the jurisdiction of a particular government.

https://schema.org/AdultOrientedEnumerat.label: AdultOrientedEnumeration
https://schema.org/AdultOrientedEnumerat.comment: Enumeration of considerations that make a product relevant or potentially restricted for adults only.

https://schema.org/AdvertiserContentArti.label: AdvertiserContentArticle
https://schema.org/AdvertiserContentArti.comment: An Article that an external entity has paid to place or to produce to its specifications. Includes advertorials, sponsored content, native advertising and other paid content.

https://schema.org/AerobicActivity.label: AerobicActivity
https://schema.org/AerobicActivity.comment: Physical activity of relatively low intensity that depends primarily on the aerobic energy-generating process; during activity, the aerobic metabolism uses oxygen to adequately meet energy demands during exercise.

https://schema.org/AggregateOffer.label: AggregateOffer
https://schema.org/AggregateOffer.comment:
When a single product is associated with multiple offers (for example, the same pair of shoes is offered by different merchants), then AggregateOffer can be used.

Note: AggregateOffers are normally expected to associate multiple offers that all share the same defined businessFunction value, or default to http://purl.org/goodrelations/v1#Sell if businessFunction is not explicitly defined.

https://schema.org/AggregateRating.label: AggregateRating
https://schema.org/AggregateRating.comment: The average rating based on multiple ratings or reviews.

https://schema.org/AgreeAction.label: AgreeAction
https://schema.org/AgreeAction.comment: The act of expressing a consistency of opinion with the object. An agent agrees to/about an object (a proposition, topic or theme) with participants.

https://schema.org/Airline.label: Airline
https://schema.org/Airline.comment: An organization that provides flights for passengers.

https://schema.org/AlcoholConsideration.label: AlcoholConsideration
https://schema.org/AlcoholConsideration.comment: Item contains alcohol or promotes alcohol consumption.

https://schema.org/AlgorithmicMediaDigit.label: AlgorithmicMediaDigitalSource
https://schema.org/AlgorithmicMediaDigit.comment: Content coded as 'algorithmic media' using the IPTC digital source type vocabulary.

https://schema.org/AlgorithmicallyEnhanc.label: AlgorithmicallyEnhancedDigitalSource
https://schema.org/AlgorithmicallyEnhanc.comment: Content coded as 'algorithmically enhanced' using the IPTC digital source type vocabulary.

https://schema.org/AlignmentObject.label: AlignmentObject
https://schema.org/AlignmentObject.comment:
An intangible item that describes an alignment between a learning resource and a node in an educational framework.

Should not be used where the nature of the alignment can be described using a simple property, for example to express that a resource teaches or assesses a competency.

https://schema.org/AllWheelDriveConfigur.label: AllWheelDriveConfiguration
https://schema.org/AllWheelDriveConfigur.comment: All-wheel Drive is a transmission layout where the engine drives all four wheels.

https://schema.org/AllergiesHealthAspect.label: AllergiesHealthAspect
https://schema.org/AllergiesHealthAspect.comment: Content about the allergy-related aspects of a health topic.

https://schema.org/AllocateAction.label: AllocateAction
https://schema.org/AllocateAction.comment: The act of organizing tasks/objects/events by associating resources to it.

https://schema.org/AmpStory.label: AmpStory
https://schema.org/AmpStory.comment: A creative work with a visual storytelling format intended to be viewed online, particularly on mobile devices.

https://schema.org/AnaerobicActivity.label: AnaerobicActivity
https://schema.org/AnaerobicActivity.comment: Physical activity that is of high-intensity which utilizes the anaerobic metabolism of the body.

https://schema.org/AnalysisNewsArticle.label: AnalysisNewsArticle
https://schema.org/AnalysisNewsArticle.comment: An AnalysisNewsArticle is a NewsArticle that, while based on factual reporting, incorporates the expertise of the author/producer, offering interpretations and conclusions.

https://schema.org/AnatomicalStructure.label: AnatomicalStructure
https://schema.org/AnatomicalStructure.comment: Any part of the human body, typically a component of an anatomical system. Organs, tissues, and cells are all anatomical structures.

https://schema.org/AnatomicalSystem.label: AnatomicalSystem
https://schema.org/AnatomicalSystem.comment: An anatomical system is a group of anatomical structures that work together to perform a certain task. Anatomical systems, such as organ systems, are one organizing principle of anatomy, and can include circulatory, digestive, endocrine, integumentary, immune, lymphatic, muscular, nervous, reproductive, respiratory, skeletal, urinary, vestibular, and other systems.

https://schema.org/AndroidPlatform.label: AndroidPlatform
https://schema.org/AndroidPlatform.comment: Represents the broad notion of Android-based operating systems.

https://schema.org/Anesthesia.label: Anesthesia
https://schema.org/Anesthesia.comment: A specific branch of medical science that pertains to study of anesthetics and their application.

https://schema.org/Answer.label: Answer
https://schema.org/Answer.comment: An answer offered to a question; perhaps correct, perhaps opinionated or wrong.

https://schema.org/Apartment.label: Apartment
https://schema.org/Apartment.comment: An apartment (in American English) or flat (in British English) is a self-contained housing unit (a type of residential real estate) that occupies only part of a building (source: Wikipedia, the free encyclopedia, see http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Apartment).

https://schema.org/AppendAction.label: AppendAction
https://schema.org/AppendAction.comment: The act of inserting at the end if an ordered collection.

https://schema.org/ApplyAction.label: ApplyAction
https://schema.org/ApplyAction.comment:
The act of registering to an organization/service without the guarantee to receive it.

Related actions:

  • RegisterAction: Unlike RegisterAction, ApplyAction has no guarantees that the application will be accepted.

https://schema.org/ApprovedIndication.label: ApprovedIndication
https://schema.org/ApprovedIndication.comment: An indication for a medical therapy that has been formally specified or approved by a regulatory body that regulates use of the therapy; for example, the US FDA approves indications for most drugs in the US.

https://schema.org/ArchiveComponent.label: ArchiveComponent
https://schema.org/ArchiveComponent.comment: An intangible type to be applied to any archive content, carrying with it a set of properties required to describe archival items and collections.

https://schema.org/ArchiveOrganization.label: ArchiveOrganization
https://schema.org/ArchiveOrganization.comment: An organization with archival holdings. An organization which keeps and preserves archival material and typically makes it accessible to the public.

https://schema.org/ArriveAction.label: ArriveAction
https://schema.org/ArriveAction.comment: The act of arriving at a place. An agent arrives at a destination from a fromLocation, optionally with participants.

https://schema.org/Artery.label: Artery
https://schema.org/Artery.comment: A type of blood vessel that specifically carries blood away from the heart.

https://schema.org/Article.label: Article
https://schema.org/Article.comment:
An article, such as a news article or piece of investigative report. Newspapers and magazines have articles of many different types and this is intended to cover them all.

See also blog post.

https://schema.org/AskAction.label: AskAction
https://schema.org/AskAction.comment:
The act of posing a question / favor to someone.

Related actions:

  • ReplyAction: Appears generally as a response to AskAction.

https://schema.org/AskPublicNewsArticle.label: AskPublicNewsArticle
https://schema.org/AskPublicNewsArticle.comment: A NewsArticle expressing an open call by a NewsMediaOrganization asking the public for input, insights, clarifications, anecdotes, documentation, etc., on an issue, for reporting purposes.

https://schema.org/AssessAction.label: AssessAction
https://schema.org/AssessAction.comment: The act of forming one's opinion, reaction or sentiment.

https://schema.org/AssignAction.label: AssignAction
https://schema.org/AssignAction.comment: The act of allocating an action/event/task to some destination (someone or something).

https://schema.org/Atlas.label: Atlas
https://schema.org/Atlas.comment: A collection or bound volume of maps, charts, plates or tables, physical or in media form illustrating any subject.

https://schema.org/Attorney.label: Attorney
https://schema.org/Attorney.comment:
Professional service: Attorney.

This type is deprecated - LegalService is more inclusive and less ambiguous.

https://schema.org/Audience.label: Audience
https://schema.org/Audience.comment: Intended audience for an item, i.e. the group for whom the item was created.

https://schema.org/AudioObjectSnapshot.label: AudioObjectSnapshot
https://schema.org/AudioObjectSnapshot.comment: A specific and exact (byte-for-byte) version of an AudioObject. Two byte-for-byte identical files, for the purposes of this type, considered identical. If they have different embedded metadata the files will differ. Different external facts about the files, e.g. creator or dateCreated that aren't represented in their actual content, do not affect this notion of identity.

https://schema.org/AudiobookFormat.label: AudiobookFormat
https://schema.org/AudiobookFormat.comment: Book format: Audiobook. This is an enumerated value for use with the bookFormat property. There is also a type 'Audiobook' in the bib extension which includes Audiobook specific properties.

https://schema.org/AuthoritativeLegalVal.label: AuthoritativeLegalValue
https://schema.org/AuthoritativeLegalVal.comment: Indicates that the publisher gives some special status to the publication of the document. ("The Queens Printer" version of a UK Act of Parliament, or the PDF version of a Directive published by the EU Office of Publications.) Something "Authoritative" is considered to be also OfficialLegalValue.

https://schema.org/AuthorizeAction.label: AuthorizeAction
https://schema.org/AuthorizeAction.comment: The act of granting permission to an object.

https://schema.org/Ayurvedic.label: Ayurvedic
https://schema.org/Ayurvedic.comment: A system of medicine that originated in India over thousands of years and that focuses on integrating and balancing the body, mind, and spirit.

https://schema.org/BackOrder.label: BackOrder
https://schema.org/BackOrder.comment: Indicates that the item is available on back order.

https://schema.org/BackgroundNewsArticle.label: BackgroundNewsArticle
https://schema.org/BackgroundNewsArticle.comment: A NewsArticle providing historical context, definition and detail on a specific topic (aka "explainer" or "backgrounder"). For example, an in-depth article or frequently-asked-questions (FAQ) document on topics such as Climate Change or the European Union. Other kinds of background material from a non-news setting are often described using Book or Article, in particular ScholarlyArticle. See also NewsArticle for related vocabulary from a learning/education perspective.

https://schema.org/Bacteria.label: Bacteria
https://schema.org/Bacteria.comment: Pathogenic bacteria that cause bacterial infection.

https://schema.org/Balance.label: Balance
https://schema.org/Balance.comment: Physical activity that is engaged to help maintain posture and balance.

https://schema.org/BankAccount.label: BankAccount
https://schema.org/BankAccount.comment: A product or service offered by a bank whereby one may deposit, withdraw or transfer money and in some cases be paid interest.

https://schema.org/Barcode.label: Barcode
https://schema.org/Barcode.comment: An image of a visual machine-readable code such as a barcode or QR code.

https://schema.org/BasicIncome.label: BasicIncome
https://schema.org/BasicIncome.comment: BasicIncome: this is a benefit for basic income.

https://schema.org/BedAndBreakfast.label: BedAndBreakfast
https://schema.org/BedAndBreakfast.comment:
Bed and breakfast.

See also the dedicated document on the use of schema.org for marking up hotels and other forms of accommodations.

https://schema.org/BedDetails.label: BedDetails
https://schema.org/BedDetails.comment: An entity holding detailed information about the available bed types, e.g. the quantity of twin beds for a hotel room. For the single case of just one bed of a certain type, you can use bed directly with a text. See also BedType (under development).

https://schema.org/BedType.label: BedType
https://schema.org/BedType.comment: A type of bed. This is used for indicating the bed or beds available in an accommodation.

https://schema.org/BefriendAction.label: BefriendAction
https://schema.org/BefriendAction.comment:
The act of forming a personal connection with someone (object) mutually/bidirectionally/symmetrically.

Related actions:

  • FollowAction: Unlike FollowAction, BefriendAction implies that the connection is reciprocal.

https://schema.org/BenefitsHealthAspect.label: BenefitsHealthAspect
https://schema.org/BenefitsHealthAspect.comment: Content about the benefits and advantages of usage or utilization of topic.

https://schema.org/BioChemEntity.label: BioChemEntity
https://schema.org/BioChemEntity.comment: Any biological, chemical, or biochemical thing. For example: a protein; a gene; a chemical; a synthetic chemical.

https://schema.org/Blog.label: Blog
https://schema.org/Blog.comment: A blog, sometimes known as a "weblog". Note that the individual posts (BlogPostings) in a Blog are often colloquially referred to by the same term.

https://schema.org/BloodTest.label: BloodTest
https://schema.org/BloodTest.comment: A medical test performed on a sample of a patient's blood.

https://schema.org/BoardingPolicyType.label: BoardingPolicyType
https://schema.org/BoardingPolicyType.comment: A type of boarding policy used by an airline.

https://schema.org/BoatReservation.label: BoatReservation
https://schema.org/BoatReservation.comment:
A reservation for boat travel.

Note: This type is for information about actual reservations, e.g. in confirmation emails or HTML pages with individual confirmations of reservations. For offers of tickets, use Offer.

https://schema.org/BoatTerminal.label: BoatTerminal
https://schema.org/BoatTerminal.comment: A terminal for boats, ships, and other water vessels.

https://schema.org/BoatTrip.label: BoatTrip
https://schema.org/BoatTrip.comment: A trip on a commercial ferry line.

https://schema.org/BodyMeasurementArm.label: BodyMeasurementArm
https://schema.org/BodyMeasurementArm.comment: Arm length (measured between arms/shoulder line intersection and the prominent wrist bone). Used, for example, to fit shirts.

https://schema.org/BodyMeasurementBust.label: BodyMeasurementBust
https://schema.org/BodyMeasurementBust.comment: Maximum girth of bust. Used, for example, to fit women's suits.

https://schema.org/BodyMeasurementChest.label: BodyMeasurementChest
https://schema.org/BodyMeasurementChest.comment: Maximum girth of chest. Used, for example, to fit men's suits.

https://schema.org/BodyMeasurementFoot.label: BodyMeasurementFoot
https://schema.org/BodyMeasurementFoot.comment: Foot length (measured between end of the most prominent toe and the most prominent part of the heel). Used, for example, to measure socks.

https://schema.org/BodyMeasurementHand.label: BodyMeasurementHand
https://schema.org/BodyMeasurementHand.comment: Maximum hand girth (measured over the knuckles of the open right hand excluding thumb, fingers together). Used, for example, to fit gloves.

https://schema.org/BodyMeasurementHead.label: BodyMeasurementHead
https://schema.org/BodyMeasurementHead.comment: Maximum girth of head above the ears. Used, for example, to fit hats.

https://schema.org/BodyMeasurementHeight.label: BodyMeasurementHeight
https://schema.org/BodyMeasurementHeight.comment: Body height (measured between crown of head and soles of feet). Used, for example, to fit jackets.

https://schema.org/BodyMeasurementHips.label: BodyMeasurementHips
https://schema.org/BodyMeasurementHips.comment: Girth of hips (measured around the buttocks). Used, for example, to fit skirts.

https://schema.org/BodyMeasurementInside.label: BodyMeasurementInsideLeg
https://schema.org/BodyMeasurementInside.comment: Inside leg (measured between crotch and soles of feet). Used, for example, to fit pants.

https://schema.org/BodyMeasurementNeck.label: BodyMeasurementNeck
https://schema.org/BodyMeasurementNeck.comment: Girth of neck. Used, for example, to fit shirts.

https://schema.org/BodyMeasurementTypeEn.label: BodyMeasurementTypeEnumeration
https://schema.org/BodyMeasurementTypeEn.comment: Enumerates types (or dimensions) of a person's body measurements, for example for fitting of clothes.

https://schema.org/BodyMeasurementUnderb.label: BodyMeasurementUnderbust
https://schema.org/BodyMeasurementUnderb.comment: Girth of body just below the bust. Used, for example, to fit women's swimwear.

https://schema.org/BodyMeasurementWaist.label: BodyMeasurementWaist
https://schema.org/BodyMeasurementWaist.comment: Girth of natural waistline (between hip bones and lower ribs). Used, for example, to fit pants.

https://schema.org/BodyMeasurementWeight.label: BodyMeasurementWeight
https://schema.org/BodyMeasurementWeight.comment: Body weight. Used, for example, to measure pantyhose.

https://schema.org/BodyOfWater.label: BodyOfWater
https://schema.org/BodyOfWater.comment: A body of water, such as a sea, ocean, or lake.

https://schema.org/Bone.label: Bone
https://schema.org/Bone.comment: Rigid connective tissue that comprises up the skeletal structure of the human body.

https://schema.org/BookFormatType.label: BookFormatType
https://schema.org/BookFormatType.comment: The publication format of the book.

https://schema.org/BookSeries.label: BookSeries
https://schema.org/BookSeries.comment: A series of books. Included books can be indicated with the hasPart property.

https://schema.org/BorrowAction.label: BorrowAction
https://schema.org/BorrowAction.comment:
The act of obtaining an object under an agreement to return it at a later date. Reciprocal of LendAction.

Related actions:

  • LendAction: Reciprocal of BorrowAction.

https://schema.org/BrainStructure.label: BrainStructure
https://schema.org/BrainStructure.comment: Any anatomical structure which pertains to the soft nervous tissue functioning as the coordinating center of sensation and intellectual and nervous activity.

https://schema.org/Brand.label: Brand
https://schema.org/Brand.comment: A brand is a name used by an organization or business person for labeling a product, product group, or similar.

https://schema.org/BreadcrumbList.label: BreadcrumbList
https://schema.org/BreadcrumbList.comment:
A BreadcrumbList is an ItemList consisting of a chain of linked Web pages, typically described using at least their URL and their name, and typically ending with the current page.

The position property is used to reconstruct the order of the items in a BreadcrumbList. The convention is that a breadcrumb list has an itemListOrder of ItemListOrderAscending (lower values listed first), and that the first items in this list correspond to the "top" or beginning of the breadcrumb trail, e.g. with a site or section homepage. The specific values of 'position' are not assigned meaning for a BreadcrumbList, but they should be integers, e.g. beginning with '1' for the first item in the list.

https://schema.org/BroadcastChannel.label: BroadcastChannel
https://schema.org/BroadcastChannel.comment: A unique instance of a BroadcastService on a CableOrSatelliteService lineup.

https://schema.org/BroadcastEvent.label: BroadcastEvent
https://schema.org/BroadcastEvent.comment: An over the air or online broadcast event.

https://schema.org/BroadcastFrequencySpe.label: BroadcastFrequencySpecification
https://schema.org/BroadcastFrequencySpe.comment: The frequency in MHz and the modulation used for a particular BroadcastService.

https://schema.org/BroadcastService.label: BroadcastService
https://schema.org/BroadcastService.comment: A delivery service through which content is provided via broadcast over the air or online.

https://schema.org/BrokerageAccount.label: BrokerageAccount
https://schema.org/BrokerageAccount.comment: An account that allows an investor to deposit funds and place investment orders with a licensed broker or brokerage firm.

https://schema.org/BusOrCoach.label: BusOrCoach
https://schema.org/BusOrCoach.comment: A bus (also omnibus or autobus) is a road vehicle designed to carry passengers. Coaches are luxury buses, usually in service for long distance travel.

https://schema.org/BusReservation.label: BusReservation
https://schema.org/BusReservation.comment:
A reservation for bus travel.

Note: This type is for information about actual reservations, e.g. in confirmation emails or HTML pages with individual confirmations of reservations. For offers of tickets, use Offer.

https://schema.org/BusTrip.label: BusTrip
https://schema.org/BusTrip.comment: A trip on a commercial bus line.

https://schema.org/BusinessAudience.label: BusinessAudience
https://schema.org/BusinessAudience.comment: A set of characteristics belonging to businesses, e.g. who compose an item's target audience.

https://schema.org/BusinessEntityType.label: BusinessEntityType
https://schema.org/BusinessEntityType.comment:
A business entity type is a conceptual entity representing the legal form, the size, the main line of business, the position in the value chain, or any combination thereof, of an organization or business person.

Commonly used values:

  • http://purl.org/goodrelations/v1#Business
  • http://purl.org/goodrelations/v1#Enduser
  • http://purl.org/goodrelations/v1#PublicInstitution
  • http://purl.org/goodrelations/v1#Reseller

https://schema.org/BusinessFunction.label: BusinessFunction
https://schema.org/BusinessFunction.comment:
The business function specifies the type of activity or access (i.e., the bundle of rights) offered by the organization or business person through the offer. Typical are sell, rental or lease, maintenance or repair, manufacture / produce, recycle / dispose, engineering / construction, or installation. Proprietary specifications of access rights are also instances of this class.

Commonly used values:

  • http://purl.org/goodrelations/v1#ConstructionInstallation
  • http://purl.org/goodrelations/v1#Dispose
  • http://purl.org/goodrelations/v1#LeaseOut
  • http://purl.org/goodrelations/v1#Maintain
  • http://purl.org/goodrelations/v1#ProvideService
  • http://purl.org/goodrelations/v1#Repair
  • http://purl.org/goodrelations/v1#Sell
  • http://purl.org/goodrelations/v1#Buy

https://schema.org/BusinessSupport.label: BusinessSupport
https://schema.org/BusinessSupport.comment: BusinessSupport: this is a benefit for supporting businesses.

https://schema.org/BuyAction.label: BuyAction
https://schema.org/BuyAction.comment: The act of giving money to a seller in exchange for goods or services rendered. An agent buys an object, product, or service from a seller for a price. Reciprocal of SellAction.

https://schema.org/ByBankTransferInAdvan.label: ByBankTransferInAdvance
https://schema.org/ByBankTransferInAdvan.comment: Payment in advance by bank transfer, equivalent to http://purl.org/goodrelations/v1#ByBankTransferInAdvance.

https://schema.org/ByInvoice.label: ByInvoice
https://schema.org/ByInvoice.comment: Payment by invoice, typically after the goods were delivered, equivalent to http://purl.org/goodrelations/v1#ByInvoice.

https://schema.org/CDCPMDRecord.label: CDCPMDRecord
https://schema.org/CDCPMDRecord.comment: A CDCPMDRecord is a data structure representing a record in a CDC tabular data format used for hospital data reporting. See documentation for details, and the linked CDC materials for authoritative definitions used as the source here.

https://schema.org/COD.label: COD
https://schema.org/COD.comment: Cash on Delivery (COD) payment, equivalent to http://purl.org/goodrelations/v1#COD.

https://schema.org/CableOrSatelliteServi.label: CableOrSatelliteService
https://schema.org/CableOrSatelliteServi.comment: A service which provides access to media programming like TV or radio. Access may be via cable or satellite.

https://schema.org/Campground.label: Campground
https://schema.org/Campground.comment:
A camping site, campsite, or Campground is a place used for overnight stay in the outdoors, typically containing individual CampingPitch locations.

In British English a campsite is an area, usually divided into a number of pitches, where people can camp overnight using tents or camper vans or caravans; this British English use of the word is synonymous with the American English expression campground. In American English the term campsite generally means an area where an individual, family, group, or military unit can pitch a tent or park a camper; a campground may contain many campsites (source: Wikipedia, see https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Campsite).

See also the dedicated document on the use of schema.org for marking up hotels and other forms of accommodations.

https://schema.org/CampingPitch.label: CampingPitch
https://schema.org/CampingPitch.comment:
A CampingPitch is an individual place for overnight stay in the outdoors, typically being part of a larger camping site, or Campground.

In British English a campsite, or campground, is an area, usually divided into a number of pitches, where people can camp overnight using tents or camper vans or caravans; this British English use of the word is synonymous with the American English expression campground. In American English the term campsite generally means an area where an individual, family, group, or military unit can pitch a tent or park a camper; a campground may contain many campsites. (Source: Wikipedia, see https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Campsite.)

See also the dedicated document on the use of schema.org for marking up hotels and other forms of accommodations.

https://schema.org/Canal.label: Canal
https://schema.org/Canal.comment: A canal, like the Panama Canal.

https://schema.org/CancelAction.label: CancelAction
https://schema.org/CancelAction.comment:
The act of asserting that a future event/action is no longer going to happen.

Related actions:

  • ConfirmAction: The antonym of CancelAction.

https://schema.org/Car.label: Car
https://schema.org/Car.comment: A car is a wheeled, self-powered motor vehicle used for transportation.

https://schema.org/CarUsageType.label: CarUsageType
https://schema.org/CarUsageType.comment: A value indicating a special usage of a car, e.g. commercial rental, driving school, or as a taxi.

https://schema.org/Cardiovascular.label: Cardiovascular
https://schema.org/Cardiovascular.comment: A specific branch of medical science that pertains to diagnosis and treatment of disorders of heart and vasculature.

https://schema.org/CardiovascularExam.label: CardiovascularExam
https://schema.org/CardiovascularExam.comment: Cardiovascular system assessment with clinical examination.

https://schema.org/CaseSeries.label: CaseSeries
https://schema.org/CaseSeries.comment: A case series (also known as a clinical series) is a medical research study that tracks patients with a known exposure given similar treatment or examines their medical records for exposure and outcome. A case series can be retrospective or prospective and usually involves a smaller number of patients than the more powerful case-control studies or randomized controlled trials. Case series may be consecutive or non-consecutive, depending on whether all cases presenting to the reporting authors over a period of time were included, or only a selection.

https://schema.org/Cash.label: Cash
https://schema.org/Cash.comment: Payment using cash, on premises, equivalent to http://purl.org/goodrelations/v1#Cash.

https://schema.org/CategoryCodeSet.label: CategoryCodeSet
https://schema.org/CategoryCodeSet.comment: A set of Category Code values.

https://schema.org/CausesHealthAspect.label: CausesHealthAspect
https://schema.org/CausesHealthAspect.comment: Information about the causes and main actions that gave rise to the topic.

https://schema.org/Certification.label: Certification
https://schema.org/Certification.comment: A Certification is an official and authoritative statement about a subject, for example a product, service, person, or organization. A certification is typically issued by an indendent certification body, for example a professional organization or government. It formally attests certain characteristics about the subject, for example Organizations can be ISO certified, Food products can be certified Organic or Vegan, a Person can be a certified professional, a Place can be certified for food processing. There are certifications for many domains: regulatory, organizational, recycling, food, efficiency, educational, ecological, etc. A certification is a form of credential, as are accreditations and licenses. Mapped from the gs1:CertificationDetails class in the GS1 Web Vocabulary.

https://schema.org/CertificationActive.label: CertificationActive
https://schema.org/CertificationActive.comment: Specifies that a certification is active.

https://schema.org/CertificationInactive.label: CertificationInactive
https://schema.org/CertificationInactive.comment: Specifies that a certification is inactive (no longer in effect).

https://schema.org/CertificationStatusEn.label: CertificationStatusEnumeration
https://schema.org/CertificationStatusEn.comment: Enumerates the different statuses of a Certification (Active and Inactive).

https://schema.org/Chapter.label: Chapter
https://schema.org/Chapter.comment: One of the sections into which a book is divided. A chapter usually has a section number or a name.

https://schema.org/CharitableIncorporate.label: CharitableIncorporatedOrganization
https://schema.org/CharitableIncorporate.comment: CharitableIncorporatedOrganization: Non-profit type referring to a Charitable Incorporated Organization (UK).

https://schema.org/CheckAction.label: CheckAction
https://schema.org/CheckAction.comment: An agent inspects, determines, investigates, inquires, or examines an object's accuracy, quality, condition, or state.

https://schema.org/CheckInAction.label: CheckInAction
https://schema.org/CheckInAction.comment:
The act of an agent communicating (service provider, social media, etc) their arrival by registering/confirming for a previously reserved service (e.g. flight check-in) or at a place (e.g. hotel), possibly resulting in a result (boarding pass, etc).

Related actions:

  • CheckOutAction: The antonym of CheckInAction.
  • ArriveAction: Unlike ArriveAction, CheckInAction implies that the agent is informing/confirming the start of a previously reserved service.
  • ConfirmAction: Unlike ConfirmAction, CheckInAction implies that the agent is informing/confirming the start of a previously reserved service rather than its validity/existence.

https://schema.org/CheckInAdvance.label: CheckInAdvance
https://schema.org/CheckInAdvance.comment: Payment in advance by sending a check, equivalent to http://purl.org/goodrelations/v1#CheckInAdvance.

https://schema.org/CheckOutAction.label: CheckOutAction
https://schema.org/CheckOutAction.comment:
The act of an agent communicating (service provider, social media, etc) their departure of a previously reserved service (e.g. flight check-in) or place (e.g. hotel).

Related actions:

  • CheckInAction: The antonym of CheckOutAction.
  • DepartAction: Unlike DepartAction, CheckOutAction implies that the agent is informing/confirming the end of a previously reserved service.
  • CancelAction: Unlike CancelAction, CheckOutAction implies that the agent is informing/confirming the end of a previously reserved service.

https://schema.org/ChemicalSubstance.label: ChemicalSubstance
https://schema.org/ChemicalSubstance.comment: A chemical substance is 'a portion of matter of constant composition, composed of molecular entities of the same type or of different types' (source: ChEBI:59999).

https://schema.org/Chiropractic.label: Chiropractic
https://schema.org/Chiropractic.comment: A system of medicine focused on the relationship between the body's structure, mainly the spine, and its functioning.

https://schema.org/ChooseAction.label: ChooseAction
https://schema.org/ChooseAction.comment: The act of expressing a preference from a set of options or a large or unbounded set of choices/options.

https://schema.org/CivicStructure.label: CivicStructure
https://schema.org/CivicStructure.comment: A public structure, such as a town hall or concert hall.

https://schema.org/Claim.label: Claim
https://schema.org/Claim.comment:
A Claim in Schema.org represents a specific, factually-oriented claim that could be the itemReviewed in a ClaimReview. The content of a claim can be summarized with the text property. Variations on well known claims can have their common identity indicated via sameAs links, and summarized with a name. Ideally, a Claim description includes enough contextual information to minimize the risk of ambiguity or inclarity. In practice, many claims are better understood in the context in which they appear or the interpretations provided by claim reviews.

Beyond ClaimReview, the Claim type can be associated with related creative works - for example a ScholarlyArticle or Question might be about some Claim.

At this time, Schema.org does not define any types of relationship between claims. This is a natural area for future exploration.

https://schema.org/ClaimReview.label: ClaimReview
https://schema.org/ClaimReview.comment: A fact-checking review of claims made (or reported) in some creative work (referenced via itemReviewed).

https://schema.org/Class.label: Class
https://schema.org/Class.comment: A class, also often called a 'Type'; equivalent to rdfs:Class.

https://schema.org/CleaningFee.label: CleaningFee
https://schema.org/CleaningFee.comment: Represents the cleaning fee part of the total price for an offered product, for example a vacation rental.

https://schema.org/Clinician.label: Clinician
https://schema.org/Clinician.comment: Medical clinicians, including practicing physicians and other medical professionals involved in clinical practice.

https://schema.org/Clip.label: Clip
https://schema.org/Clip.comment: A short TV or radio program or a segment/part of a program.

https://schema.org/CoOp.label: CoOp
https://schema.org/CoOp.comment: Play mode: CoOp. Co-operative games, where you play on the same team with friends.

https://schema.org/Code.label: Code
https://schema.org/Code.comment: Computer programming source code. Example: Full (compile ready) solutions, code snippet samples, scripts, templates.

https://schema.org/CohortStudy.label: CohortStudy
https://schema.org/CohortStudy.comment: Also known as a panel study. A cohort study is a form of longitudinal study used in medicine and social science. It is one type of study design and should be compared with a cross-sectional study.  A cohort is a group of people who share a common characteristic or experience within a defined period (e.g., are born, leave school, lose their job, are exposed to a drug or a vaccine, etc.). The comparison group may be the general population from which the cohort is drawn, or it may be another cohort of persons thought to have had little or no exposure to the substance under investigation, but otherwise similar. Alternatively, subgroups within the cohort may be compared with each other.

https://schema.org/Collection.label: Collection
https://schema.org/Collection.comment: A collection of items, e.g. creative works or products.

https://schema.org/CollegeOrUniversity.label: CollegeOrUniversity
https://schema.org/CollegeOrUniversity.comment: A college, university, or other third-level educational institution.

https://schema.org/ComicCoverArt.label: ComicCoverArt
https://schema.org/ComicCoverArt.comment: The artwork on the cover of a comic.

https://schema.org/ComicIssue.label: ComicIssue
https://schema.org/ComicIssue.comment:
Individual comic issues are serially published as
        part of a larger series. For the sake of consistency, even one-shot issues
        belong to a series comprised of a single issue. All comic issues can be
        uniquely identified by: the combination of the name and volume number of the
        series to which the issue belongs; the issue number; and the variant
        description of the issue (if any).

https://schema.org/ComicSeries.label: ComicSeries
https://schema.org/ComicSeries.comment:
A sequential publication of comic stories under a
        unifying title, for example "The Amazing Spider-Man" or "Groo the
        Wanderer".

https://schema.org/ComicStory.label: ComicStory
https://schema.org/ComicStory.comment:
The term "story" is any indivisible, re-printable
        unit of a comic, including the interior stories, covers, and backmatter. Most
        comics have at least two stories: a cover (ComicCoverArt) and an interior story.

https://schema.org/Comment.label: Comment
https://schema.org/Comment.comment: A comment on an item - for example, a comment on a blog post. The comment's content is expressed via the text property, and its topic via about, properties shared with all CreativeWorks.

https://schema.org/CommentAction.label: CommentAction
https://schema.org/CommentAction.comment: The act of generating a comment about a subject.

https://schema.org/CommentPermission.label: CommentPermission
https://schema.org/CommentPermission.comment: Permission to add comments to the document.

https://schema.org/CommunicateAction.label: CommunicateAction
https://schema.org/CommunicateAction.comment: The act of conveying information to another person via a communication medium (instrument) such as speech, email, or telephone conversation.

https://schema.org/CommunityHealth.label: CommunityHealth
https://schema.org/CommunityHealth.comment: A field of public health focusing on improving health characteristics of a defined population in relation with their geographical or environment areas.

https://schema.org/CompleteDataFeed.label: CompleteDataFeed
https://schema.org/CompleteDataFeed.comment:
A CompleteDataFeed is a DataFeed whose standard representation includes content for every item currently in the feed.

This is the equivalent of Atom's element as defined in Feed Paging and Archiving RFC 5005, for example (and as defined for Atom), when using data from a feed that represents a collection of items that varies over time (e.g. "Top Twenty Records") there is no need to have newer entries mixed in alongside older, obsolete entries. By marking this feed as a CompleteDataFeed, old entries can be safely discarded when the feed is refreshed, since we can assume the feed has provided descriptions for all current items.

https://schema.org/CompletedActionStatus.label: CompletedActionStatus
https://schema.org/CompletedActionStatus.comment: An action that has already taken place.

https://schema.org/CompositeCaptureDigit.label: CompositeCaptureDigitalSource
https://schema.org/CompositeCaptureDigit.comment: Content coded as 'composite capture' using the IPTC digital source type vocabulary.

https://schema.org/CompositeDigitalSourc.label: CompositeDigitalSource
https://schema.org/CompositeDigitalSourc.comment: Content coded as 'algorithmic media' using the IPTC digital source type vocabulary.

https://schema.org/CompositeSyntheticDig.label: CompositeSyntheticDigitalSource
https://schema.org/CompositeSyntheticDig.comment: Content coded as 'composite synthetic' using the IPTC digital source type vocabulary.

https://schema.org/CompositeWithTrainedA.label: CompositeWithTrainedAlgorithmicMediaDigitalSource
https://schema.org/CompositeWithTrainedA.comment: Content coded as 'composite with trained algorithmic media' using the IPTC digital source type vocabulary.

https://schema.org/CompoundPriceSpecific.label: CompoundPriceSpecification
https://schema.org/CompoundPriceSpecific.comment: A compound price specification is one that bundles multiple prices that all apply in combination for different dimensions of consumption. Use the name property of the attached unit price specification for indicating the dimension of a price component (e.g. "electricity" or "final cleaning").

https://schema.org/ComputerLanguage.label: ComputerLanguage
https://schema.org/ComputerLanguage.comment: This type covers computer programming languages such as Scheme and Lisp, as well as other language-like computer representations. Natural languages are best represented with the Language type.

https://schema.org/ConfirmAction.label: ConfirmAction
https://schema.org/ConfirmAction.comment:
The act of notifying someone that a future event/action is going to happen as expected.

Related actions:

  • CancelAction: The antonym of ConfirmAction.

https://schema.org/Consortium.label: Consortium
https://schema.org/Consortium.comment: A Consortium is a membership Organization whose members are typically Organizations.

https://schema.org/ConstraintNode.label: ConstraintNode
https://schema.org/ConstraintNode.comment: The ConstraintNode type is provided to support usecases in which a node in a structured data graph is described with properties which appear to describe a single entity, but are being used in a situation where they serve a more abstract purpose. A ConstraintNode can be described using constraintProperty and numConstraints. These constraint properties can serve a variety of purposes, and their values may sometimes be understood to indicate sets of possible values rather than single, exact and specific values.

https://schema.org/ContactPoint.label: ContactPoint
https://schema.org/ContactPoint.comment: A contact point—for example, a Customer Complaints department.

https://schema.org/ContactPointOption.label: ContactPointOption
https://schema.org/ContactPointOption.comment: Enumerated options related to a ContactPoint.

https://schema.org/ContagiousnessHealthA.label: ContagiousnessHealthAspect
https://schema.org/ContagiousnessHealthA.comment: Content about contagion mechanisms and contagiousness information over the topic.

https://schema.org/Continent.label: Continent
https://schema.org/Continent.comment: One of the continents (for example, Europe or Africa).

https://schema.org/ControlAction.label: ControlAction
https://schema.org/ControlAction.comment: An agent controls a device or application.

https://schema.org/Conversation.label: Conversation
https://schema.org/Conversation.comment: One or more messages between organizations or people on a particular topic. Individual messages can be linked to the conversation with isPartOf or hasPart properties.

https://schema.org/CorrectionComment.label: CorrectionComment
https://schema.org/CorrectionComment.comment: A comment that corrects CreativeWork.

https://schema.org/Course.label: Course
https://schema.org/Course.comment: A description of an educational course which may be offered as distinct instances which take place at different times or take place at different locations, or be offered through different media or modes of study. An educational course is a sequence of one or more educational events and/or creative works which aims to build knowledge, competence or ability of learners.

https://schema.org/CourseInstance.label: CourseInstance
https://schema.org/CourseInstance.comment: An instance of a Course which is distinct from other instances because it is offered at a different time or location or through different media or modes of study or to a specific section of students.

https://schema.org/CoverArt.label: CoverArt
https://schema.org/CoverArt.comment: The artwork on the outer surface of a CreativeWork.

https://schema.org/CovidTestingFacility.label: CovidTestingFacility
https://schema.org/CovidTestingFacility.comment: A CovidTestingFacility is a MedicalClinic where testing for the COVID-19 Coronavirus disease is available. If the facility is being made available from an established Pharmacy, Hotel, or other non-medical organization, multiple types can be listed. This makes it easier to re-use existing schema.org information about that place, e.g. contact info, address, opening hours. Note that in an emergency, such information may not always be reliable.

https://schema.org/CreateAction.label: CreateAction
https://schema.org/CreateAction.comment: The act of deliberately creating/producing/generating/building a result out of the agent.

https://schema.org/CreativeWork.label: CreativeWork
https://schema.org/CreativeWork.comment: The most generic kind of creative work, including books, movies, photographs, software programs, etc.

https://schema.org/CreativeWorkSeason.label: CreativeWorkSeason
https://schema.org/CreativeWorkSeason.comment: A media season, e.g. TV, radio, video game etc.

https://schema.org/CreativeWorkSeries.label: CreativeWorkSeries
https://schema.org/CreativeWorkSeries.comment:
A CreativeWorkSeries in schema.org is a group of related items, typically but not necessarily of the same kind. CreativeWorkSeries are usually organized into some order, often chronological. Unlike ItemList which is a general purpose data structure for lists of things, the emphasis with CreativeWorkSeries is on published materials (written e.g. books and periodicals, or media such as TV, radio and games).

Specific subtypes are available for describing TVSeries, RadioSeries, MovieSeries, BookSeries, Periodical and VideoGameSeries. In each case, the hasPart / isPartOf properties can be used to relate the CreativeWorkSeries to its parts. The general CreativeWorkSeries type serves largely just to organize these more specific and practical subtypes.

It is common for properties applicable to an item from the series to be usefully applied to the containing group. Schema.org attempts to anticipate some of these cases, but publishers should be free to apply properties of the series parts to the series as a whole wherever they seem appropriate.

https://schema.org/CreditCard.label: CreditCard
https://schema.org/CreditCard.comment:
A card payment method of a particular brand or name. Used to mark up a particular payment method and/or the financial product/service that supplies the card account.

Commonly used values:

  • http://purl.org/goodrelations/v1#AmericanExpress
  • http://purl.org/goodrelations/v1#DinersClub
  • http://purl.org/goodrelations/v1#Discover
  • http://purl.org/goodrelations/v1#JCB
  • http://purl.org/goodrelations/v1#MasterCard
  • http://purl.org/goodrelations/v1#VISA

https://schema.org/CriticReview.label: CriticReview
https://schema.org/CriticReview.comment: A CriticReview is a more specialized form of Review written or published by a source that is recognized for its reviewing activities. These can include online columns, travel and food guides, TV and radio shows, blogs and other independent Web sites. CriticReviews are typically more in-depth and professionally written. For simpler, casually written user/visitor/viewer/customer reviews, it is more appropriate to use the UserReview type. Review aggregator sites such as Metacritic already separate out the site's user reviews from selected critic reviews that originate from third-party sources.

https://schema.org/CrossSectional.label: CrossSectional
https://schema.org/CrossSectional.comment: Studies carried out on pre-existing data (usually from 'snapshot' surveys), such as that collected by the Census Bureau. Sometimes called Prevalence Studies.

https://schema.org/CurrencyConversionSer.label: CurrencyConversionService
https://schema.org/CurrencyConversionSer.comment: A service to convert funds from one currency to another currency.

https://schema.org/DDxElement.label: DDxElement
https://schema.org/DDxElement.comment: An alternative, closely-related condition typically considered later in the differential diagnosis process along with the signs that are used to distinguish it.

https://schema.org/DamagedCondition.label: DamagedCondition
https://schema.org/DamagedCondition.comment: Indicates that the item is damaged.

https://schema.org/DanceGroup.label: DanceGroup
https://schema.org/DanceGroup.comment: A dance group—for example, the Alvin Ailey Dance Theater or Riverdance.

https://schema.org/DangerousGoodConsider.label: DangerousGoodConsideration
https://schema.org/DangerousGoodConsider.comment: The item is dangerous and requires careful handling and/or special training of the user. See also the UN Model Classification defining the 9 classes of dangerous goods such as explosives, gases, flammables, and more.

https://schema.org/DataDownload.label: DataDownload
https://schema.org/DataDownload.comment: All or part of a Dataset in downloadable form.

https://schema.org/DataDrivenMediaDigita.label: DataDrivenMediaDigitalSource
https://schema.org/DataDrivenMediaDigita.comment: Content coded as 'data driven media' using the IPTC digital source type vocabulary.

https://schema.org/DataFeed.label: DataFeed
https://schema.org/DataFeed.comment: A single feed providing structured information about one or more entities or topics.

https://schema.org/DataFeedItem.label: DataFeedItem
https://schema.org/DataFeedItem.comment: A single item within a larger data feed.

https://schema.org/DataType.label: DataType
https://schema.org/DataType.comment: The basic data types such as Integers, Strings, etc.

https://schema.org/Dataset.label: Dataset
https://schema.org/Dataset.comment: A body of structured information describing some topic(s) of interest.

https://schema.org/Date.label: Date
https://schema.org/Date.comment: A date value in ISO 8601 date format.

https://schema.org/DateTime.label: DateTime
https://schema.org/DateTime.comment: A combination of date and time of day in the form [-]CCYY-MM-DDThh:mm:ss[Z|(+|-)hh:mm] (see Chapter 5.4 of ISO 8601).

https://schema.org/DatedMoneySpecificati.label: DatedMoneySpecification
https://schema.org/DatedMoneySpecificati.comment: A DatedMoneySpecification represents monetary values with optional start and end dates. For example, this could represent an employee's salary over a specific period of time. Note: This type has been superseded by MonetaryAmount, use of that type is recommended.

https://schema.org/DayOfWeek.label: DayOfWeek
https://schema.org/DayOfWeek.comment:
The day of the week, e.g. used to specify to which day the opening hours of an OpeningHoursSpecification refer.

Originally, URLs from GoodRelations were used (for Monday, Tuesday, Wednesday, Thursday, Friday, Saturday, Sunday plus a special entry for PublicHolidays); these have now been integrated directly into schema.org.

https://schema.org/DeactivateAction.label: DeactivateAction
https://schema.org/DeactivateAction.comment: The act of stopping or deactivating a device or application (e.g. stopping a timer or turning off a flashlight).

https://schema.org/DecontextualizedConte.label: DecontextualizedContent
https://schema.org/DecontextualizedConte.comment:
Content coded 'missing context' in a MediaReview, considered in the context of how it was published or shared.

For a VideoObject to be 'missing context': Presenting unaltered video in an inaccurate manner that misrepresents the footage. For example, using incorrect dates or locations, altering the transcript or sharing brief clips from a longer video to mislead viewers. (A video rated 'original' can also be missing context.)

For an ImageObject to be 'missing context': Presenting unaltered images in an inaccurate manner to misrepresent the image and mislead the viewer. For example, a common tactic is using an unaltered image but saying it came from a different time or place. (An image rated 'original' can also be missing context.)

For an ImageObject with embedded text to be 'missing context': An unaltered image presented in an inaccurate manner to misrepresent the image and mislead the viewer. For example, a common tactic is using an unaltered image but saying it came from a different time or place. (An 'original' image with inaccurate text would generally fall in this category.)

For an AudioObject to be 'missing context': Unaltered audio presented in an inaccurate manner that misrepresents it. For example, using incorrect dates or locations, or sharing brief clips from a longer recording to mislead viewers. (Audio rated original can also be missing context.)

https://schema.org/DefenceEstablishment.label: DefenceEstablishment
https://schema.org/DefenceEstablishment.comment: A defence establishment, such as an army or navy base.

https://schema.org/DefinedRegion.label: DefinedRegion
https://schema.org/DefinedRegion.comment:
A DefinedRegion is a geographic area defined by potentially arbitrary (rather than political, administrative or natural geographical) criteria. Properties are provided for defining a region by reference to sets of postal codes.

Examples: a delivery destination when shopping. Region where regional pricing is configured.

Requirement 1: Country: US States: "NY", "CA"

Requirement 2: Country: US PostalCode Set: { [94000-94585], [97000, 97999], [13000, 13599]} { [12345, 12345], [78945, 78945], } Region = state, canton, prefecture, autonomous community...

https://schema.org/DefinedTerm.label: DefinedTerm
https://schema.org/DefinedTerm.comment: A word, name, acronym, phrase, etc. with a formal definition. Often used in the context of category or subject classification, glossaries or dictionaries, product or creative work types, etc. Use the name property for the term being defined, use termCode if the term has an alpha-numeric code allocated, use description to provide the definition of the term.

https://schema.org/DefinedTermSet.label: DefinedTermSet
https://schema.org/DefinedTermSet.comment: A set of defined terms, for example a set of categories or a classification scheme, a glossary, dictionary or enumeration.

https://schema.org/DefinitiveLegalValue.label: DefinitiveLegalValue
https://schema.org/DefinitiveLegalValue.comment: Indicates a document for which the text is conclusively what the law says and is legally binding. (E.g. the digitally signed version of an Official Journal.) Something "Definitive" is considered to be also AuthoritativeLegalValue.

https://schema.org/DeleteAction.label: DeleteAction
https://schema.org/DeleteAction.comment: The act of editing a recipient by removing one of its objects.

https://schema.org/DeliveryChargeSpecifi.label: DeliveryChargeSpecification
https://schema.org/DeliveryChargeSpecifi.comment: The price for the delivery of an offer using a particular delivery method.

https://schema.org/DeliveryEvent.label: DeliveryEvent
https://schema.org/DeliveryEvent.comment: An event involving the delivery of an item.

https://schema.org/DeliveryMethod.label: DeliveryMethod
https://schema.org/DeliveryMethod.comment:
A delivery method is a standardized procedure for transferring the product or service to the destination of fulfillment chosen by the customer. Delivery methods are characterized by the means of transportation used, and by the organization or group that is the contracting party for the sending organization or person.

Commonly used values:

  • http://purl.org/goodrelations/v1#DeliveryModeDirectDownload
  • http://purl.org/goodrelations/v1#DeliveryModeFreight
  • http://purl.org/goodrelations/v1#DeliveryModeMail
  • http://purl.org/goodrelations/v1#DeliveryModeOwnFleet
  • http://purl.org/goodrelations/v1#DeliveryModePickUp
  • http://purl.org/goodrelations/v1#DHL
  • http://purl.org/goodrelations/v1#FederalExpress
  • http://purl.org/goodrelations/v1#UPS

https://schema.org/DeliveryTimeSettings.label: DeliveryTimeSettings
https://schema.org/DeliveryTimeSettings.comment: A DeliveryTimeSettings represents re-usable pieces of shipping information, relating to timing. It is designed for publication on an URL that may be referenced via the shippingSettingsLink property of an OfferShippingDetails. Several occurrences can be published, distinguished (and identified/referenced) by their different values for transitTimeLabel.

https://schema.org/Demand.label: Demand
https://schema.org/Demand.comment: A demand entity represents the public, not necessarily binding, not necessarily exclusive, announcement by an organization or person to seek a certain type of goods or services. For describing demand using this type, the very same properties used for Offer apply.

https://schema.org/DemoGameAvailability.label: DemoGameAvailability
https://schema.org/DemoGameAvailability.comment: Indicates demo game availability, i.e. a somehow limited demonstration of the full game.

https://schema.org/Dentistry.label: Dentistry
https://schema.org/Dentistry.comment: A branch of medicine that is involved in the dental care.

https://schema.org/DepartAction.label: DepartAction
https://schema.org/DepartAction.comment: The act of  departing from a place. An agent departs from a fromLocation for a destination, optionally with participants.

https://schema.org/DepositAccount.label: DepositAccount
https://schema.org/DepositAccount.comment: A type of Bank Account with a main purpose of depositing funds to gain interest or other benefits.

https://schema.org/Dermatologic.label: Dermatologic
https://schema.org/Dermatologic.comment: Something relating to or practicing dermatology.

https://schema.org/Dermatology.label: Dermatology
https://schema.org/Dermatology.comment: A specific branch of medical science that pertains to diagnosis and treatment of disorders of skin.

https://schema.org/DesktopWebPlatform.label: DesktopWebPlatform
https://schema.org/DesktopWebPlatform.comment: Represents the broad notion of 'desktop' browsers as a Web Platform.

https://schema.org/DiabeticDiet.label: DiabeticDiet
https://schema.org/DiabeticDiet.comment: A diet appropriate for people with diabetes.

https://schema.org/Diagnostic.label: Diagnostic
https://schema.org/Diagnostic.comment: A medical device used for diagnostic purposes.

https://schema.org/DiagnosticLab.label: DiagnosticLab
https://schema.org/DiagnosticLab.comment: A medical laboratory that offers on-site or off-site diagnostic services.

https://schema.org/DiagnosticProcedure.label: DiagnosticProcedure
https://schema.org/DiagnosticProcedure.comment: A medical procedure intended primarily for diagnostic, as opposed to therapeutic, purposes.

https://schema.org/Diet.label: Diet
https://schema.org/Diet.comment: A strategy of regulating the intake of food to achieve or maintain a specific health-related goal.

https://schema.org/DietNutrition.label: DietNutrition
https://schema.org/DietNutrition.comment: Dietetics and nutrition as a medical specialty.

https://schema.org/DietarySupplement.label: DietarySupplement
https://schema.org/DietarySupplement.comment: A product taken by mouth that contains a dietary ingredient intended to supplement the diet. Dietary ingredients may include vitamins, minerals, herbs or other botanicals, amino acids, and substances such as enzymes, organ tissues, glandulars and metabolites.

https://schema.org/DigitalArtDigitalSour.label: DigitalArtDigitalSource
https://schema.org/DigitalArtDigitalSour.comment: Content coded as 'digital art' using the IPTC digital source type vocabulary.

https://schema.org/DigitalCaptureDigital.label: DigitalCaptureDigitalSource
https://schema.org/DigitalCaptureDigital.comment: Content coded as 'digital capture' using the IPTC digital source type vocabulary.

https://schema.org/DigitalDocumentPermis.label: DigitalDocumentPermission
https://schema.org/DigitalDocumentPermis.comment: A permission for a particular person or group to access a particular file.

https://schema.org/DigitalDocumentPermis.label: DigitalDocumentPermissionType
https://schema.org/DigitalDocumentPermis.comment: A type of permission which can be granted for accessing a digital document.

https://schema.org/DigitalPlatformEnumer.label: DigitalPlatformEnumeration
https://schema.org/DigitalPlatformEnumer.comment: Enumerates some common technology platforms, for use with properties such as actionPlatform. It is not supposed to be comprehensive - when a suitable code is not enumerated here, textual or URL values can be used instead. These codes are at a fairly high level and do not deal with versioning and other nuance. Additional codes can be suggested in github.

https://schema.org/DirectDebit.label: DirectDebit
https://schema.org/DirectDebit.comment: Payment in advance by direct debit from the bank, equivalent to http://purl.org/goodrelations/v1#DirectDebit.

https://schema.org/DisabilitySupport.label: DisabilitySupport
https://schema.org/DisabilitySupport.comment: DisabilitySupport: this is a benefit for disability support.

https://schema.org/DisagreeAction.label: DisagreeAction
https://schema.org/DisagreeAction.comment: The act of expressing a difference of opinion with the object. An agent disagrees to/about an object (a proposition, topic or theme) with participants.

https://schema.org/Discontinued.label: Discontinued
https://schema.org/Discontinued.comment: Indicates that the item has been discontinued.

https://schema.org/DiscoverAction.label: DiscoverAction
https://schema.org/DiscoverAction.comment: The act of discovering/finding an object.

https://schema.org/DiscussionForumPostin.label: DiscussionForumPosting
https://schema.org/DiscussionForumPostin.comment: A posting to a discussion forum.

https://schema.org/DislikeAction.label: DislikeAction
https://schema.org/DislikeAction.comment: The act of expressing a negative sentiment about the object. An agent dislikes an object (a proposition, topic or theme) with participants.

https://schema.org/Distance.label: Distance
https://schema.org/Distance.comment: Properties that take Distances as values are of the form '<Number> <Length unit of measure>'. E.g., '7 ft'.

https://schema.org/DistanceFee.label: DistanceFee
https://schema.org/DistanceFee.comment: Represents the distance fee (e.g., price per km or mile) part of the total price for an offered product, for example a car rental.

https://schema.org/DonateAction.label: DonateAction
https://schema.org/DonateAction.comment: The act of providing goods, services, or money without compensation, often for philanthropic reasons.

https://schema.org/DoseSchedule.label: DoseSchedule
https://schema.org/DoseSchedule.comment: A specific dosing schedule for a drug or supplement.

https://schema.org/DoubleBlindedTrial.label: DoubleBlindedTrial
https://schema.org/DoubleBlindedTrial.comment: A trial design in which neither the researcher nor the patient knows the details of the treatment the patient was randomly assigned to.

https://schema.org/DownloadAction.label: DownloadAction
https://schema.org/DownloadAction.comment: The act of downloading an object.

https://schema.org/Downpayment.label: Downpayment
https://schema.org/Downpayment.comment: Represents the downpayment (up-front payment) price component of the total price for an offered product that has additional installment payments.

https://schema.org/DrawAction.label: DrawAction
https://schema.org/DrawAction.comment: The act of producing a visual/graphical representation of an object, typically with a pen/pencil and paper as instruments.

https://schema.org/Drawing.label: Drawing
https://schema.org/Drawing.comment: A picture or diagram made with a pencil, pen, or crayon rather than paint.

https://schema.org/DriveWheelConfigurati.label: DriveWheelConfigurationValue
https://schema.org/DriveWheelConfigurati.comment: A value indicating which roadwheels will receive torque.

https://schema.org/DrivingSchoolVehicleU.label: DrivingSchoolVehicleUsage
https://schema.org/DrivingSchoolVehicleU.comment: Indicates the usage of the vehicle for driving school.

https://schema.org/Drug.label: Drug
https://schema.org/Drug.comment: A chemical or biologic substance, used as a medical therapy, that has a physiological effect on an organism. Here the term drug is used interchangeably with the term medicine although clinical knowledge makes a clear difference between them.

https://schema.org/DrugClass.label: DrugClass
https://schema.org/DrugClass.comment: A class of medical drugs, e.g., statins. Classes can represent general pharmacological class, common mechanisms of action, common physiological effects, etc.

https://schema.org/DrugCost.label: DrugCost
https://schema.org/DrugCost.comment: The cost per unit of a medical drug. Note that this type is not meant to represent the price in an offer of a drug for sale; see the Offer type for that. This type will typically be used to tag wholesale or average retail cost of a drug, or maximum reimbursable cost. Costs of medical drugs vary widely depending on how and where they are paid for, so while this type captures some of the variables, costs should be used with caution by consumers of this schema's markup.

https://schema.org/DrugCostCategory.label: DrugCostCategory
https://schema.org/DrugCostCategory.comment: Enumerated categories of medical drug costs.

https://schema.org/DrugLegalStatus.label: DrugLegalStatus
https://schema.org/DrugLegalStatus.comment: The legal availability status of a medical drug.

https://schema.org/DrugPregnancyCategory.label: DrugPregnancyCategory
https://schema.org/DrugPregnancyCategory.comment: Categories that represent an assessment of the risk of fetal injury due to a drug or pharmaceutical used as directed by the mother during pregnancy.

https://schema.org/DrugPrescriptionStatu.label: DrugPrescriptionStatus
https://schema.org/DrugPrescriptionStatu.comment: Indicates whether this drug is available by prescription or over-the-counter.

https://schema.org/DrugStrength.label: DrugStrength
https://schema.org/DrugStrength.comment: A specific strength in which a medical drug is available in a specific country.

https://schema.org/EUEnergyEfficiencyCat.label: EUEnergyEfficiencyCategoryA
https://schema.org/EUEnergyEfficiencyCat.comment: Represents EU Energy Efficiency Class A as defined in EU energy labeling regulations.

https://schema.org/EUEnergyEfficiencyCat.label: EUEnergyEfficiencyCategoryA1Plus
https://schema.org/EUEnergyEfficiencyCat.comment: Represents EU Energy Efficiency Class A+ as defined in EU energy labeling regulations.

https://schema.org/EUEnergyEfficiencyCat.label: EUEnergyEfficiencyCategoryA2Plus
https://schema.org/EUEnergyEfficiencyCat.comment: Represents EU Energy Efficiency Class A++ as defined in EU energy labeling regulations.

https://schema.org/EUEnergyEfficiencyCat.label: EUEnergyEfficiencyCategoryA3Plus
https://schema.org/EUEnergyEfficiencyCat.comment: Represents EU Energy Efficiency Class A+++ as defined in EU energy labeling regulations.

https://schema.org/EUEnergyEfficiencyCat.label: EUEnergyEfficiencyCategoryB
https://schema.org/EUEnergyEfficiencyCat.comment: Represents EU Energy Efficiency Class B as defined in EU energy labeling regulations.

https://schema.org/EUEnergyEfficiencyCat.label: EUEnergyEfficiencyCategoryC
https://schema.org/EUEnergyEfficiencyCat.comment: Represents EU Energy Efficiency Class C as defined in EU energy labeling regulations.

https://schema.org/EUEnergyEfficiencyCat.label: EUEnergyEfficiencyCategoryD
https://schema.org/EUEnergyEfficiencyCat.comment: Represents EU Energy Efficiency Class D as defined in EU energy labeling regulations.

https://schema.org/EUEnergyEfficiencyCat.label: EUEnergyEfficiencyCategoryE
https://schema.org/EUEnergyEfficiencyCat.comment: Represents EU Energy Efficiency Class E as defined in EU energy labeling regulations.

https://schema.org/EUEnergyEfficiencyCat.label: EUEnergyEfficiencyCategoryF
https://schema.org/EUEnergyEfficiencyCat.comment: Represents EU Energy Efficiency Class F as defined in EU energy labeling regulations.

https://schema.org/EUEnergyEfficiencyCat.label: EUEnergyEfficiencyCategoryG
https://schema.org/EUEnergyEfficiencyCat.comment: Represents EU Energy Efficiency Class G as defined in EU energy labeling regulations.

https://schema.org/EUEnergyEfficiencyEnu.label: EUEnergyEfficiencyEnumeration
https://schema.org/EUEnergyEfficiencyEnu.comment: Enumerates the EU energy efficiency classes A-G as well as A+, A++, and A+++ as defined in EU directive 2017/1369.

https://schema.org/Ear.label: Ear
https://schema.org/Ear.comment: Ear function assessment with clinical examination.

https://schema.org/EatAction.label: EatAction
https://schema.org/EatAction.comment: The act of swallowing solid objects.

https://schema.org/EditedOrCroppedConten.label: EditedOrCroppedContent
https://schema.org/EditedOrCroppedConten.comment:
Content coded 'edited or cropped content' in a MediaReview, considered in the context of how it was published or shared.

For a VideoObject to be 'edited or cropped content': The video has been edited or rearranged. This category applies to time edits, including editing multiple videos together to alter the story being told or editing out large portions from a video.

For an ImageObject to be 'edited or cropped content': Presenting a part of an image from a larger whole to mislead the viewer.

For an ImageObject with embedded text to be 'edited or cropped content': Presenting a part of an image from a larger whole to mislead the viewer.

For an AudioObject to be 'edited or cropped content': The audio has been edited or rearranged. This category applies to time edits, including editing multiple audio clips together to alter the story being told or editing out large portions from the recording.

https://schema.org/EducationalOccupation.label: EducationalOccupationalCredential
https://schema.org/EducationalOccupation.comment: An educational or occupational credential. A diploma, academic degree, certification, qualification, badge, etc., that may be awarded to a person or other entity that meets the requirements defined by the credentialer.

https://schema.org/EducationalOccupation.label: EducationalOccupationalProgram
https://schema.org/EducationalOccupation.comment: A program offered by an institution which determines the learning progress to achieve an outcome, usually a credential like a degree or certificate. This would define a discrete set of opportunities (e.g., job, courses) that together constitute a program with a clear start, end, set of requirements, and transition to a new occupational opportunity (e.g., a job), or sometimes a higher educational opportunity (e.g., an advanced degree).

https://schema.org/EffectivenessHealthAs.label: EffectivenessHealthAspect
https://schema.org/EffectivenessHealthAs.comment: Content about the effectiveness-related aspects of a health topic.

https://schema.org/Emergency.label: Emergency
https://schema.org/Emergency.comment: A specific branch of medical science that deals with the evaluation and initial treatment of medical conditions caused by trauma or sudden illness.

https://schema.org/EmergencyService.label: EmergencyService
https://schema.org/EmergencyService.comment: An emergency service, such as a fire station or ER.

https://schema.org/EmployeeRole.label: EmployeeRole
https://schema.org/EmployeeRole.comment: A subclass of OrganizationRole used to describe employee relationships.

https://schema.org/EmployerAggregateRati.label: EmployerAggregateRating
https://schema.org/EmployerAggregateRati.comment: An aggregate rating of an Organization related to its role as an employer.

https://schema.org/EmployerReview.label: EmployerReview
https://schema.org/EmployerReview.comment: An EmployerReview is a review of an Organization regarding its role as an employer, written by a current or former employee of that organization.

https://schema.org/Endocrine.label: Endocrine
https://schema.org/Endocrine.comment: A specific branch of medical science that pertains to diagnosis and treatment of disorders of endocrine glands and their secretions.

https://schema.org/EndorsementRating.label: EndorsementRating
https://schema.org/EndorsementRating.comment:
An EndorsementRating is a rating that expresses some level of endorsement, for example inclusion in a "critic's pick" blog, a "Like" or "+1" on a social network. It can be considered the result of an EndorseAction in which the object of the action is rated positively by some agent. As is common elsewhere in schema.org, it is sometimes more useful to describe the results of such an action without explicitly describing the Action.

An EndorsementRating may be part of a numeric scale or organized system, but this is not required: having an explicit type for indicating a positive, endorsement rating is particularly useful in the absence of numeric scales as it helps consumers understand that the rating is broadly positive.

https://schema.org/Energy.label: Energy
https://schema.org/Energy.comment: Properties that take Energy as values are of the form '<Number> <Energy unit of measure>'.

https://schema.org/EnergyConsumptionDeta.label: EnergyConsumptionDetails
https://schema.org/EnergyConsumptionDeta.comment: EnergyConsumptionDetails represents information related to the energy efficiency of a product that consumes energy. The information that can be provided is based on international regulations such as for example EU directive 2017/1369 for energy labeling and the Energy labeling rule under the Energy Policy and Conservation Act (EPCA) in the US.

https://schema.org/EnergyEfficiencyEnume.label: EnergyEfficiencyEnumeration
https://schema.org/EnergyEfficiencyEnume.comment: Enumerates energy efficiency levels (also known as "classes" or "ratings") and certifications that are part of several international energy efficiency standards.

https://schema.org/EnergyStarEnergyEffic.label: EnergyStarEnergyEfficiencyEnumeration
https://schema.org/EnergyStarEnergyEffic.comment: Used to indicate whether a product is EnergyStar certified.

https://schema.org/EngineSpecification.label: EngineSpecification
https://schema.org/EngineSpecification.comment: Information about the engine of the vehicle. A vehicle can have multiple engines represented by multiple engine specification entities.

https://schema.org/EntryPoint.label: EntryPoint
https://schema.org/EntryPoint.comment: An entry point, within some Web-based protocol.

https://schema.org/Enumeration.label: Enumeration
https://schema.org/Enumeration.comment: Lists or enumerationsfor example, a list of cuisines or music genres, etc.

https://schema.org/Episode.label: Episode
https://schema.org/Episode.comment: A media episode (e.g. TV, radio, video game) which can be part of a series or season.

https://schema.org/Event.label: Event
https://schema.org/Event.comment: An event happening at a certain time and location, such as a concert, lecture, or festival. Ticketing information may be added via the offers property. Repeated events may be structured as separate Event objects.

https://schema.org/EventAttendanceModeEn.label: EventAttendanceModeEnumeration
https://schema.org/EventAttendanceModeEn.comment: An EventAttendanceModeEnumeration value is one of potentially several modes of organising an event, relating to whether it is online or offline.

https://schema.org/EventCancelled.label: EventCancelled
https://schema.org/EventCancelled.comment: The event has been cancelled. If the event has multiple startDate values, all are assumed to be cancelled. Either startDate or previousStartDate may be used to specify the event's cancelled date(s).

https://schema.org/EventMovedOnline.label: EventMovedOnline
https://schema.org/EventMovedOnline.comment: Indicates that the event was changed to allow online participation. See eventAttendanceMode for specifics of whether it is now fully or partially online.

https://schema.org/EventPostponed.label: EventPostponed
https://schema.org/EventPostponed.comment: The event has been postponed and no new date has been set. The event's previousStartDate should be set.

https://schema.org/EventRescheduled.label: EventRescheduled
