https://schema.org/Nonprofit501c9.comment: Nonprofit501c9: Non-profit type referring to Voluntary Employee Beneficiary Associations.

https://schema.org/Nonprofit501d.label: Nonprofit501d
https://schema.org/Nonprofit501d.comment: Nonprofit501d: Non-profit type referring to Religious and Apostolic Associations.

https://schema.org/Nonprofit501e.label: Nonprofit501e
https://schema.org/Nonprofit501e.comment: Nonprofit501e: Non-profit type referring to Cooperative Hospital Service Organizations.

https://schema.org/Nonprofit501f.label: Nonprofit501f
https://schema.org/Nonprofit501f.comment: Nonprofit501f: Non-profit type referring to Cooperative Service Organizations.

https://schema.org/Nonprofit501k.label: Nonprofit501k
https://schema.org/Nonprofit501k.comment: Nonprofit501k: Non-profit type referring to Child Care Organizations.

https://schema.org/Nonprofit501n.label: Nonprofit501n
https://schema.org/Nonprofit501n.comment: Nonprofit501n: Non-profit type referring to Charitable Risk Pools.

https://schema.org/Nonprofit501q.label: Nonprofit501q
https://schema.org/Nonprofit501q.comment: Nonprofit501q: Non-profit type referring to Credit Counseling Organizations.

https://schema.org/Nonprofit527.label: Nonprofit527
https://schema.org/Nonprofit527.comment: Nonprofit527: Non-profit type referring to political organizations.

https://schema.org/NonprofitANBI.label: NonprofitANBI
https://schema.org/NonprofitANBI.comment: NonprofitANBI: Non-profit type referring to a Public Benefit Organization (NL).

https://schema.org/NonprofitSBBI.label: NonprofitSBBI
https://schema.org/NonprofitSBBI.comment: NonprofitSBBI: Non-profit type referring to a Social Interest Promoting Institution (NL).

https://schema.org/NonprofitType.label: NonprofitType
https://schema.org/NonprofitType.comment: NonprofitType enumerates several kinds of official non-profit types of which a non-profit organization can be.

https://schema.org/Nose.label: Nose
https://schema.org/Nose.comment: Nose function assessment with clinical examination.

https://schema.org/NotInForce.label: NotInForce
https://schema.org/NotInForce.comment: Indicates that a legislation is currently not in force.

https://schema.org/NoteDigitalDocument.label: NoteDigitalDocument
https://schema.org/NoteDigitalDocument.comment: A file containing a note, primarily for the author.

https://schema.org/Number.label: Number
https://schema.org/Number.comment:
Data type: Number.

Usage guidelines:

  • Use values from 0123456789 (Unicode 'DIGIT ZERO' (U+0030) to 'DIGIT NINE' (U+0039)) rather than superficially similar Unicode symbols.
  • Use '.' (Unicode 'FULL STOP' (U+002E)) rather than ',' to indicate a decimal point. Avoid using these symbols as a readability separator.

https://schema.org/Nursing.label: Nursing
https://schema.org/Nursing.comment: A health profession of a person formally educated and trained in the care of the sick or infirm person.

https://schema.org/OTC.label: OTC
https://schema.org/OTC.comment: The character of a medical substance, typically a medicine, of being available over the counter or not.

https://schema.org/Observation.label: Observation
https://schema.org/Observation.comment:
Instances of the class Observation are used to specify observations about an entity at a particular time. The principal properties of an Observation are observationAbout, measuredProperty, statType, [[value] and observationDate and measuredProperty. Some but not all Observations represent a QuantitativeValue. Quantitative observations can be about a StatisticalVariable, which is an abstract specification about which we can make observations that are grounded at a particular location and time.

Observations can also encode a subset of simple RDF-like statements (its observationAbout, a StatisticalVariable, defining the measuredPoperty; its observationAbout property indicating the entity the statement is about, and value )

In the context of a quantitative knowledge graph, typical properties could include measuredProperty, observationAbout, observationDate, value, unitCode, unitText, measurementMethod.

https://schema.org/Obstetric.label: Obstetric
https://schema.org/Obstetric.comment: A specific branch of medical science that specializes in the care of women during the prenatal and postnatal care and with the delivery of the child.

https://schema.org/Occupation.label: Occupation
https://schema.org/Occupation.comment: A profession, may involve prolonged training and/or a formal qualification.

https://schema.org/OccupationalActivity.label: OccupationalActivity
https://schema.org/OccupationalActivity.comment: Any physical activity engaged in for job-related purposes. Examples may include waiting tables, maid service, carrying a mailbag, picking fruits or vegetables, construction work, etc.

https://schema.org/OccupationalExperienc.label: OccupationalExperienceRequirements
https://schema.org/OccupationalExperienc.comment: Indicates employment-related experience requirements, e.g. monthsOfExperience.

https://schema.org/OccupationalTherapy.label: OccupationalTherapy
https://schema.org/OccupationalTherapy.comment: A treatment of people with physical, emotional, or social problems, using purposeful activity to help them overcome or learn to deal with their problems.

https://schema.org/Offer.label: Offer
https://schema.org/Offer.comment:
An offer to transfer some rights to an item or to provide a service for example, an offer to sell tickets to an event, to rent the DVD of a movie, to stream a TV show over the internet, to repair a motorcycle, or to loan a book.

Note: As the businessFunction property, which identifies the form of offer (e.g. sell, lease, repair, dispose), defaults to http://purl.org/goodrelations/v1#Sell; an Offer without a defined businessFunction value can be assumed to be an offer to sell.

For GTIN-related fields, see Check Digit calculator and validation guide from GS1.

https://schema.org/OfferCatalog.label: OfferCatalog
https://schema.org/OfferCatalog.comment: An OfferCatalog is an ItemList that contains related Offers and/or further OfferCatalogs that are offeredBy the same provider.

https://schema.org/OfferForLease.label: OfferForLease
https://schema.org/OfferForLease.comment: An OfferForLease in Schema.org represents an Offer to lease out something, i.e. an Offer whose businessFunction is lease out. See Good Relations for background on the underlying concepts.

https://schema.org/OfferForPurchase.label: OfferForPurchase
https://schema.org/OfferForPurchase.comment: An OfferForPurchase in Schema.org represents an Offer to sell something, i.e. an Offer whose businessFunction is sell. See Good Relations for background on the underlying concepts.

https://schema.org/OfferItemCondition.label: OfferItemCondition
https://schema.org/OfferItemCondition.comment: A list of possible conditions for the item.

https://schema.org/OfferShippingDetails.label: OfferShippingDetails
https://schema.org/OfferShippingDetails.comment:
OfferShippingDetails represents information about shipping destinations.

Multiple of these entities can be used to represent different shipping rates for different destinations:

One entity for Alaska/Hawaii. A different one for continental US. A different one for all France.

Multiple of these entities can be used to represent different shipping costs and delivery times.

Two entities that are identical but differ in rate and time:

E.g. Cheaper and slower: $5 in 5-7 days or Fast and expensive: $15 in 1-2 days.

https://schema.org/OfficialLegalValue.label: OfficialLegalValue
https://schema.org/OfficialLegalValue.comment: All the documents published by an official publisher should have at least the legal value level "OfficialLegalValue". This indicates that the document was published by an organisation with the public task of making it available (e.g. a consolidated version of an EU directive published by the EU Office of Publications).

https://schema.org/OfflineEventAttendanc.label: OfflineEventAttendanceMode
https://schema.org/OfflineEventAttendanc.comment: OfflineEventAttendanceMode - an event that is primarily conducted offline.

https://schema.org/OfflinePermanently.label: OfflinePermanently
https://schema.org/OfflinePermanently.comment: Game server status: OfflinePermanently. Server is offline and not available.

https://schema.org/OfflineTemporarily.label: OfflineTemporarily
https://schema.org/OfflineTemporarily.comment: Game server status: OfflineTemporarily. Server is offline now but it can be online soon.

https://schema.org/OnDemandEvent.label: OnDemandEvent
https://schema.org/OnDemandEvent.comment: A publication event, e.g. catch-up TV or radio podcast, during which a program is available on-demand.

https://schema.org/OnSitePickup.label: OnSitePickup
https://schema.org/OnSitePickup.comment: A DeliveryMethod in which an item is collected on site, e.g. in a store or at a box office.

https://schema.org/Oncologic.label: Oncologic
https://schema.org/Oncologic.comment: A specific branch of medical science that deals with benign and malignant tumors, including the study of their development, diagnosis, treatment and prevention.

https://schema.org/OneTimePayments.label: OneTimePayments
https://schema.org/OneTimePayments.comment: OneTimePayments: this is a benefit for one-time payments for individuals.

https://schema.org/Online.label: Online
https://schema.org/Online.comment: Game server status: Online. Server is available.

https://schema.org/OnlineBusiness.label: OnlineBusiness
https://schema.org/OnlineBusiness.comment: A particular online business, either standalone or the online part of a broader organization. Examples include an eCommerce site, an online travel booking site, an online learning site, an online logistics and shipping provider, an online (virtual) doctor, etc.

https://schema.org/OnlineEventAttendance.label: OnlineEventAttendanceMode
https://schema.org/OnlineEventAttendance.comment: OnlineEventAttendanceMode - an event that is primarily conducted online.

https://schema.org/OnlineFull.label: OnlineFull
https://schema.org/OnlineFull.comment: Game server status: OnlineFull. Server is online but unavailable. The maximum number of players has reached.

https://schema.org/OnlineOnly.label: OnlineOnly
https://schema.org/OnlineOnly.comment: Indicates that the item is available only online.

https://schema.org/OpenTrial.label: OpenTrial
https://schema.org/OpenTrial.comment: A trial design in which the researcher knows the full details of the treatment, and so does the patient.

https://schema.org/OpeningHoursSpecifica.label: OpeningHoursSpecification
https://schema.org/OpeningHoursSpecifica.comment:
A structured value providing information about the opening hours of a place or a certain service inside a place.

The place is open if the opens property is specified, and closed otherwise.

If the value for the closes property is less than the value for the opens property then the hour range is assumed to span over the next day.

https://schema.org/OpinionNewsArticle.label: OpinionNewsArticle
https://schema.org/OpinionNewsArticle.comment: An OpinionNewsArticle is a NewsArticle that primarily expresses opinions rather than journalistic reporting of news and events. For example, a NewsArticle consisting of a column or Blog/BlogPosting entry in the Opinions section of a news publication.

https://schema.org/Optician.label: Optician
https://schema.org/Optician.comment: A store that sells reading glasses and similar devices for improving vision.

https://schema.org/Optometric.label: Optometric
https://schema.org/Optometric.comment: The science or practice of testing visual acuity and prescribing corrective lenses.

https://schema.org/Order.label: Order
https://schema.org/Order.comment: An order is a confirmation of a transaction (a receipt), which can contain multiple line items, each represented by an Offer that has been accepted by the customer.

https://schema.org/OrderAction.label: OrderAction
https://schema.org/OrderAction.comment: An agent orders an object/product/service to be delivered/sent.

https://schema.org/OrderCancelled.label: OrderCancelled
https://schema.org/OrderCancelled.comment: OrderStatus representing cancellation of an order.

https://schema.org/OrderDelivered.label: OrderDelivered
https://schema.org/OrderDelivered.comment: OrderStatus representing successful delivery of an order.

https://schema.org/OrderInTransit.label: OrderInTransit
https://schema.org/OrderInTransit.comment: OrderStatus representing that an order is in transit.

https://schema.org/OrderItem.label: OrderItem
https://schema.org/OrderItem.comment: An order item is a line of an order. It includes the quantity and shipping details of a bought offer.

https://schema.org/OrderPaymentDue.label: OrderPaymentDue
https://schema.org/OrderPaymentDue.comment: OrderStatus representing that payment is due on an order.

https://schema.org/OrderPickupAvailable.label: OrderPickupAvailable
https://schema.org/OrderPickupAvailable.comment: OrderStatus representing availability of an order for pickup.

https://schema.org/OrderProblem.label: OrderProblem
https://schema.org/OrderProblem.comment: OrderStatus representing that there is a problem with the order.

https://schema.org/OrderProcessing.label: OrderProcessing
https://schema.org/OrderProcessing.comment: OrderStatus representing that an order is being processed.

https://schema.org/OrderReturned.label: OrderReturned
https://schema.org/OrderReturned.comment: OrderStatus representing that an order has been returned.

https://schema.org/Organization.label: Organization
https://schema.org/Organization.comment: An organization such as a school, NGO, corporation, club, etc.

https://schema.org/OrganizationRole.label: OrganizationRole
https://schema.org/OrganizationRole.comment: A subclass of Role used to describe roles within organizations.

https://schema.org/OrganizeAction.label: OrganizeAction
https://schema.org/OrganizeAction.comment: The act of manipulating/administering/supervising/controlling one or more objects.

https://schema.org/OriginalMediaContent.label: OriginalMediaContent
https://schema.org/OriginalMediaContent.comment:
Content coded 'as original media content' in a MediaReview, considered in the context of how it was published or shared.

For a VideoObject to be 'original': No evidence the footage has been misleadingly altered or manipulated, though it may contain false or misleading claims.

For an ImageObject to be 'original': No evidence the image has been misleadingly altered or manipulated, though it may still contain false or misleading claims.

For an ImageObject with embedded text to be 'original': No evidence the image has been misleadingly altered or manipulated, though it may still contain false or misleading claims.

For an AudioObject to be 'original': No evidence the audio has been misleadingly altered or manipulated, though it may contain false or misleading claims.

https://schema.org/OriginalShippingFees.label: OriginalShippingFees
https://schema.org/OriginalShippingFees.comment: Specifies that the customer must pay the original shipping costs when returning a product.

https://schema.org/Osteopathic.label: Osteopathic
https://schema.org/Osteopathic.comment: A system of medicine focused on promoting the body's innate ability to heal itself.

https://schema.org/Otolaryngologic.label: Otolaryngologic
https://schema.org/Otolaryngologic.comment: A specific branch of medical science that is concerned with the ear, nose and throat and their respective disease states.

https://schema.org/OutOfStock.label: OutOfStock
https://schema.org/OutOfStock.comment: Indicates that the item is out of stock.

https://schema.org/OverviewHealthAspect.label: OverviewHealthAspect
https://schema.org/OverviewHealthAspect.comment: Overview of the content. Contains a summarized view of the topic with the most relevant information for an introduction.

https://schema.org/OwnershipInfo.label: OwnershipInfo
https://schema.org/OwnershipInfo.comment: A structured value providing information about when a certain organization or person owned a certain product.

https://schema.org/PaidLeave.label: PaidLeave
https://schema.org/PaidLeave.comment: PaidLeave: this is a benefit for paid leave.

https://schema.org/PaintAction.label: PaintAction
https://schema.org/PaintAction.comment: The act of producing a painting, typically with paint and canvas as instruments.

https://schema.org/PalliativeProcedure.label: PalliativeProcedure
https://schema.org/PalliativeProcedure.comment: A medical procedure intended primarily for palliative purposes, aimed at relieving the symptoms of an underlying health condition.

https://schema.org/ParcelDelivery.label: ParcelDelivery
https://schema.org/ParcelDelivery.comment: The delivery of a parcel either via the postal service or a commercial service.

https://schema.org/ParcelService.label: ParcelService
https://schema.org/ParcelService.comment:
A private parcel service as the delivery mode available for a certain offer.

Commonly used values:

  • http://purl.org/goodrelations/v1#DHL
  • http://purl.org/goodrelations/v1#FederalExpress
  • http://purl.org/goodrelations/v1#UPS

https://schema.org/ParentAudience.label: ParentAudience
https://schema.org/ParentAudience.comment: A set of characteristics describing parents, who can be interested in viewing some content.

https://schema.org/ParentalSupport.label: ParentalSupport
https://schema.org/ParentalSupport.comment: ParentalSupport: this is a benefit for parental support.

https://schema.org/ParkingFacility.label: ParkingFacility
https://schema.org/ParkingFacility.comment: A parking lot or other parking facility.

https://schema.org/PartiallyInForce.label: PartiallyInForce
https://schema.org/PartiallyInForce.comment: Indicates that parts of the legislation are in force, and parts are not.

https://schema.org/Pathology.label: Pathology
https://schema.org/Pathology.comment: A specific branch of medical science that is concerned with the study of the cause, origin and nature of a disease state, including its consequences as a result of manifestation of the disease. In clinical care, the term is used to designate a branch of medicine using laboratory tests to diagnose and determine the prognostic significance of illness.

https://schema.org/PathologyTest.label: PathologyTest
https://schema.org/PathologyTest.comment: A medical test performed by a laboratory that typically involves examination of a tissue sample by a pathologist.

https://schema.org/Patient.label: Patient
https://schema.org/Patient.comment: A patient is any person recipient of health care services.

https://schema.org/PatientExperienceHeal.label: PatientExperienceHealthAspect
https://schema.org/PatientExperienceHeal.comment: Content about the real life experience of patients or people that have lived a similar experience about the topic. May be forums, topics, Q-and-A and related material.

https://schema.org/PawnShop.label: PawnShop
https://schema.org/PawnShop.comment: A shop that will buy, or lend money against the security of, personal possessions.

https://schema.org/PayAction.label: PayAction
https://schema.org/PayAction.comment: An agent pays a price to a participant.

https://schema.org/PaymentAutomaticallyA.label: PaymentAutomaticallyApplied
https://schema.org/PaymentAutomaticallyA.comment: An automatic payment system is in place and will be used.

https://schema.org/PaymentCard.label: PaymentCard
https://schema.org/PaymentCard.comment: A payment method using a credit, debit, store or other card to associate the payment with an account.

https://schema.org/PaymentChargeSpecific.label: PaymentChargeSpecification
https://schema.org/PaymentChargeSpecific.comment: The costs of settling the payment using a particular payment method.

https://schema.org/PaymentComplete.label: PaymentComplete
https://schema.org/PaymentComplete.comment: The payment has been received and processed.

https://schema.org/PaymentDeclined.label: PaymentDeclined
https://schema.org/PaymentDeclined.comment: The payee received the payment, but it was declined for some reason.

https://schema.org/PaymentDue.label: PaymentDue
https://schema.org/PaymentDue.comment: The payment is due, but still within an acceptable time to be received.

https://schema.org/PaymentMethod.label: PaymentMethod
https://schema.org/PaymentMethod.comment:
A payment method is a standardized procedure for transferring the monetary amount for a purchase. Payment methods are characterized by the legal and technical structures used, and by the organization or group carrying out the transaction. The following legacy values should be accepted:

  • http://purl.org/goodrelations/v1#ByBankTransferInAdvance
  • http://purl.org/goodrelations/v1#ByInvoice
  • http://purl.org/goodrelations/v1#Cash
  • http://purl.org/goodrelations/v1#CheckInAdvance
  • http://purl.org/goodrelations/v1#COD
  • http://purl.org/goodrelations/v1#DirectDebit
  • http://purl.org/goodrelations/v1#GoogleCheckout
  • http://purl.org/goodrelations/v1#PayPal
  • http://purl.org/goodrelations/v1#PaySwarm
Structured values are recommended for newer payment methods.

https://schema.org/PaymentMethodType.label: PaymentMethodType
https://schema.org/PaymentMethodType.comment: The type of payment method, only for generic payment types, specific forms of payments, like card payment should be expressed using subclasses of PaymentMethod.

https://schema.org/PaymentPastDue.label: PaymentPastDue
https://schema.org/PaymentPastDue.comment: The payment is due and considered late.

https://schema.org/PaymentService.label: PaymentService
https://schema.org/PaymentService.comment: A Service to transfer funds from a person or organization to a beneficiary person or organization.

https://schema.org/PaymentStatusType.label: PaymentStatusType
https://schema.org/PaymentStatusType.comment: A specific payment status. For example, PaymentDue, PaymentComplete, etc.

https://schema.org/Pediatric.label: Pediatric
https://schema.org/Pediatric.comment: A specific branch of medical science that specializes in the care of infants, children and adolescents.

https://schema.org/PeopleAudience.label: PeopleAudience
https://schema.org/PeopleAudience.comment: A set of characteristics belonging to people, e.g. who compose an item's target audience.

https://schema.org/PercutaneousProcedure.label: PercutaneousProcedure
https://schema.org/PercutaneousProcedure.comment: A type of medical procedure that involves percutaneous techniques, where access to organs or tissue is achieved via needle-puncture of the skin. For example, catheter-based procedures like stent delivery.

https://schema.org/PerformAction.label: PerformAction
https://schema.org/PerformAction.comment: The act of participating in performance arts.

https://schema.org/PerformanceRole.label: PerformanceRole
https://schema.org/PerformanceRole.comment: A PerformanceRole is a Role that some entity places with regard to a theatrical performance, e.g. in a Movie, TVSeries etc.

https://schema.org/PerformingArtsTheater.label: PerformingArtsTheater
https://schema.org/PerformingArtsTheater.comment: A theater or other performing art center.

https://schema.org/PerformingGroup.label: PerformingGroup
https://schema.org/PerformingGroup.comment: A performance group, such as a band, an orchestra, or a circus.

https://schema.org/Periodical.label: Periodical
https://schema.org/Periodical.comment:
A publication in any medium issued in successive parts bearing numerical or chronological designations and intended to continue indefinitely, such as a magazine, scholarly journal, or newspaper.

See also blog post.

https://schema.org/Permit.label: Permit
https://schema.org/Permit.comment: A permit issued by an organization, e.g. a parking pass.

https://schema.org/Person.label: Person
https://schema.org/Person.comment: A person (alive, dead, undead, or fictional).

https://schema.org/PharmacySpecialty.label: PharmacySpecialty
https://schema.org/PharmacySpecialty.comment: The practice or art and science of preparing and dispensing drugs and medicines.

https://schema.org/PhoneCarrierPayment.label: PhoneCarrierPayment
https://schema.org/PhoneCarrierPayment.comment: Payment by billing via the phone carrier.

https://schema.org/PhotographAction.label: PhotographAction
https://schema.org/PhotographAction.comment: The act of capturing still images of objects using a camera.

https://schema.org/PhysicalActivity.label: PhysicalActivity
https://schema.org/PhysicalActivity.comment: Any bodily activity that enhances or maintains physical fitness and overall health and wellness. Includes activity that is part of daily living and routine, structured exercise, and exercise prescribed as part of a medical treatment or recovery plan.

https://schema.org/PhysicalActivityCateg.label: PhysicalActivityCategory
https://schema.org/PhysicalActivityCateg.comment: Categories of physical activity, organized by physiologic classification.

https://schema.org/PhysicalExam.label: PhysicalExam
https://schema.org/PhysicalExam.comment: A type of physical examination of a patient performed by a physician.

https://schema.org/PhysicalTherapy.label: PhysicalTherapy
https://schema.org/PhysicalTherapy.comment: A process of progressive physical care and rehabilitation aimed at improving a health condition.

https://schema.org/Physician.label: Physician
https://schema.org/Physician.comment: An individual physician or a physician's office considered as a MedicalOrganization.

https://schema.org/Physiotherapy.label: Physiotherapy
https://schema.org/Physiotherapy.comment: The practice of treatment of disease, injury, or deformity by physical methods such as massage, heat treatment, and exercise rather than by drugs or surgery.

https://schema.org/Place.label: Place
https://schema.org/Place.comment: Entities that have a somewhat fixed, physical extension.

https://schema.org/PlaceOfWorship.label: PlaceOfWorship
https://schema.org/PlaceOfWorship.comment: Place of worship, such as a church, synagogue, or mosque.

https://schema.org/PlanAction.label: PlanAction
https://schema.org/PlanAction.comment: The act of planning the execution of an event/task/action/reservation/plan to a future date.

https://schema.org/PlasticSurgery.label: PlasticSurgery
https://schema.org/PlasticSurgery.comment: A specific branch of medical science that pertains to therapeutic or cosmetic repair or re-formation of missing, injured or malformed tissues or body parts by manual and instrumental means.

https://schema.org/Play.label: Play
https://schema.org/Play.comment: A play is a form of literature, usually consisting of dialogue between characters, intended for theatrical performance rather than just reading. Note: A performance of a Play would be a TheaterEvent or BroadcastEvent - the Play being the workPerformed.

https://schema.org/PlayAction.label: PlayAction
https://schema.org/PlayAction.comment:
The act of playing/exercising/training/performing for enjoyment, leisure, recreation, competition or exercise.

Related actions:

  • ListenAction: Unlike ListenAction (which is under ConsumeAction), PlayAction refers to performing for an audience or at an event, rather than consuming music.
  • WatchAction: Unlike WatchAction (which is under ConsumeAction), PlayAction refers to showing/displaying for an audience or at an event, rather than consuming visual content.

https://schema.org/PlayGameAction.label: PlayGameAction
https://schema.org/PlayGameAction.comment: The act of playing a video game.

https://schema.org/PodcastEpisode.label: PodcastEpisode
https://schema.org/PodcastEpisode.comment: A single episode of a podcast series.

https://schema.org/PodcastSeason.label: PodcastSeason
https://schema.org/PodcastSeason.comment: A single season of a podcast. Many podcasts do not break down into separate seasons. In that case, PodcastSeries should be used.

https://schema.org/PodcastSeries.label: PodcastSeries
https://schema.org/PodcastSeries.comment: A podcast is an episodic series of digital audio or video files which a user can download and listen to.

https://schema.org/Podiatric.label: Podiatric
https://schema.org/Podiatric.comment: Podiatry is the care of the human foot, especially the diagnosis and treatment of foot disorders.

https://schema.org/PositiveFilmDigitalSo.label: PositiveFilmDigitalSource
https://schema.org/PositiveFilmDigitalSo.comment: Content coded as 'positive film' using the IPTC digital source type vocabulary.

https://schema.org/PostalCodeRangeSpecif.label: PostalCodeRangeSpecification
https://schema.org/PostalCodeRangeSpecif.comment: Indicates a range of postal codes, usually defined as the set of valid codes between postalCodeBegin and postalCodeEnd, inclusively.

https://schema.org/Poster.label: Poster
https://schema.org/Poster.comment: A large, usually printed placard, bill, or announcement, often illustrated, that is posted to advertise or publicize something.

https://schema.org/PotentialActionStatus.label: PotentialActionStatus
https://schema.org/PotentialActionStatus.comment: A description of an action that is supported.

https://schema.org/PreOrder.label: PreOrder
https://schema.org/PreOrder.comment: Indicates that the item is available for pre-order.

https://schema.org/PreOrderAction.label: PreOrderAction
https://schema.org/PreOrderAction.comment: An agent orders a (not yet released) object/product/service to be delivered/sent.

https://schema.org/PreSale.label: PreSale
https://schema.org/PreSale.comment: Indicates that the item is available for ordering and delivery before general availability.

https://schema.org/PregnancyHealthAspect.label: PregnancyHealthAspect
https://schema.org/PregnancyHealthAspect.comment: Content discussing pregnancy-related aspects of a health topic.

https://schema.org/PrependAction.label: PrependAction
https://schema.org/PrependAction.comment: The act of inserting at the beginning if an ordered collection.

https://schema.org/PresentationDigitalDo.label: PresentationDigitalDocument
https://schema.org/PresentationDigitalDo.comment: A file containing slides or used for a presentation.

https://schema.org/PreventionHealthAspec.label: PreventionHealthAspect
https://schema.org/PreventionHealthAspec.comment: Information about actions or measures that can be taken to avoid getting the topic or reaching a critical situation related to the topic.

https://schema.org/PreventionIndication.label: PreventionIndication
https://schema.org/PreventionIndication.comment: An indication for preventing an underlying condition, symptom, etc.

https://schema.org/PriceComponentTypeEnu.label: PriceComponentTypeEnumeration
https://schema.org/PriceComponentTypeEnu.comment: Enumerates different price components that together make up the total price for an offered product.

https://schema.org/PriceSpecification.label: PriceSpecification
https://schema.org/PriceSpecification.comment: A structured value representing a price or price range. Typically, only the subclasses of this type are used for markup. It is recommended to use MonetaryAmount to describe independent amounts of money such as a salary, credit card limits, etc.

https://schema.org/PriceTypeEnumeration.label: PriceTypeEnumeration
https://schema.org/PriceTypeEnumeration.comment: Enumerates different price types, for example list price, invoice price, and sale price.

https://schema.org/PrimaryCare.label: PrimaryCare
https://schema.org/PrimaryCare.comment: The medical care by a physician, or other health-care professional, who is the patient's first contact with the health-care system and who may recommend a specialist if necessary.

https://schema.org/PrintDigitalSource.label: PrintDigitalSource
https://schema.org/PrintDigitalSource.comment: Content coded as 'print' using the IPTC digital source type vocabulary.

https://schema.org/Prion.label: Prion
https://schema.org/Prion.comment: A prion is an infectious agent composed of protein in a misfolded form.

https://schema.org/Product.label: Product
https://schema.org/Product.comment: Any offered product or service. For example: a pair of shoes; a concert ticket; the rental of a car; a haircut; or an episode of a TV show streamed online.

https://schema.org/ProductCollection.label: ProductCollection
https://schema.org/ProductCollection.comment: A set of products (either ProductGroups or specific variants) that are listed together e.g. in an Offer.

https://schema.org/ProductGroup.label: ProductGroup
https://schema.org/ProductGroup.comment:
A ProductGroup represents a group of Products that vary only in certain well-described ways, such as by size, color, material etc.

While a ProductGroup itself is not directly offered for sale, the various varying products that it represents can be. The ProductGroup serves as a prototype or template, standing in for all of the products who have an isVariantOf relationship to it. As such, properties (including additional types) can be applied to the ProductGroup to represent characteristics shared by each of the (possibly very many) variants. Properties that reference a ProductGroup are not included in this mechanism; neither are the following specific properties variesBy, hasVariant, url.

https://schema.org/ProductModel.label: ProductModel
https://schema.org/ProductModel.comment: A datasheet or vendor specification of a product (in the sense of a prototypical description).

https://schema.org/ProductReturnEnumerat.label: ProductReturnEnumeration
https://schema.org/ProductReturnEnumerat.comment: ProductReturnEnumeration enumerates several kinds of product return policy. Note that this structure may not capture all aspects of the policy.

https://schema.org/ProductReturnFiniteRe.label: ProductReturnFiniteReturnWindow
https://schema.org/ProductReturnFiniteRe.comment: ProductReturnFiniteReturnWindow: there is a finite window for product returns.

https://schema.org/ProductReturnNotPermi.label: ProductReturnNotPermitted
https://schema.org/ProductReturnNotPermi.comment: ProductReturnNotPermitted: product returns are not permitted.

https://schema.org/ProductReturnPolicy.label: ProductReturnPolicy
https://schema.org/ProductReturnPolicy.comment: A ProductReturnPolicy provides information about product return policies associated with an Organization or Product.

https://schema.org/ProductReturnUnlimite.label: ProductReturnUnlimitedWindow
https://schema.org/ProductReturnUnlimite.comment: ProductReturnUnlimitedWindow: there is an unlimited window for product returns.

https://schema.org/ProductReturnUnspecif.label: ProductReturnUnspecified
https://schema.org/ProductReturnUnspecif.comment: ProductReturnUnspecified: a product return policy is not specified here.

https://schema.org/ProfessionalService.label: ProfessionalService
https://schema.org/ProfessionalService.comment:
Original definition: "provider of professional services."

The general ProfessionalService type for local businesses was deprecated due to confusion with Service. For reference, the types that it included were: Dentist, AccountingService, Attorney, Notary, as well as types for several kinds of HomeAndConstructionBusiness: Electrician, GeneralContractor, HousePainter, Locksmith, Plumber, RoofingContractor. LegalService was introduced as a more inclusive supertype of Attorney.

https://schema.org/PrognosisHealthAspect.label: PrognosisHealthAspect
https://schema.org/PrognosisHealthAspect.comment: Typical progression and happenings of life course of the topic.

https://schema.org/ProgramMembership.label: ProgramMembership
https://schema.org/ProgramMembership.comment: Used to describe membership in a loyalty programs (e.g. "StarAliance"), traveler clubs (e.g. "AAA"), purchase clubs ("Safeway Club"), etc.

https://schema.org/Project.label: Project
https://schema.org/Project.comment: An enterprise (potentially individual but typically collaborative), planned to achieve a particular aim. Use properties from Organization, subOrganization/parentOrganization to indicate project sub-structures.

https://schema.org/Property.label: Property
https://schema.org/Property.comment: A property, used to indicate attributes and relationships of some Thing; equivalent to rdf:Property.

https://schema.org/PropertyValue.label: PropertyValue
https://schema.org/PropertyValue.comment:
A property-value pair, e.g. representing a feature of a product or place. Use the 'name' property for the name of the property. If there is an additional human-readable version of the value, put that into the 'description' property.

Always use specific schema.org properties when a) they exist and b) you can populate them. Using PropertyValue as a substitute will typically not trigger the same effect as using the original, specific property.

https://schema.org/Protein.label: Protein
https://schema.org/Protein.comment: Protein is here used in its widest possible definition, as classes of amino acid based molecules. Amyloid-beta Protein in human (UniProt P05067), eukaryota (e.g. an OrthoDB group) or even a single molecule that one can point to are all of type :Protein. A protein can thus be a subclass of another protein, e.g. :Protein as a UniProt record can have multiple isoforms inside it which would also be :Protein. They can be imagined, synthetic, hypothetical or naturally occurring.

https://schema.org/Protozoa.label: Protozoa
https://schema.org/Protozoa.comment: Single-celled organism that causes an infection.

https://schema.org/Psychiatric.label: Psychiatric
https://schema.org/Psychiatric.comment: A specific branch of medical science that is concerned with the study, treatment, and prevention of mental illness, using both medical and psychological therapies.

https://schema.org/PsychologicalTreatmen.label: PsychologicalTreatment
https://schema.org/PsychologicalTreatmen.comment: A process of care relying upon counseling, dialogue and communication  aimed at improving a mental health condition without use of drugs.

https://schema.org/PublicHealth.label: PublicHealth
https://schema.org/PublicHealth.comment: Branch of medicine that pertains to the health services to improve and protect community health, especially epidemiology, sanitation, immunization, and preventive medicine.

https://schema.org/PublicHolidays.label: PublicHolidays
https://schema.org/PublicHolidays.comment: This stands for any day that is a public holiday; it is a placeholder for all official public holidays in some particular location. While not technically a "day of the week", it can be used with OpeningHoursSpecification. In the context of an opening hours specification it can be used to indicate opening hours on public holidays, overriding general opening hours for the day of the week on which a public holiday occurs.

https://schema.org/PublicToilet.label: PublicToilet
https://schema.org/PublicToilet.comment: A public toilet is a room or small building containing one or more toilets (and possibly also urinals) which is available for use by the general public, or by customers or employees of certain businesses.

https://schema.org/PublicationEvent.label: PublicationEvent
https://schema.org/PublicationEvent.comment: A PublicationEvent corresponds indifferently to the event of publication for a CreativeWork of any type, e.g. a broadcast event, an on-demand event, a book/journal publication via a variety of delivery media.

https://schema.org/PublicationIssue.label: PublicationIssue
https://schema.org/PublicationIssue.comment:
A part of a successively published publication such as a periodical or publication volume, often numbered, usually containing a grouping of works such as articles.

See also blog post.

https://schema.org/PublicationVolume.label: PublicationVolume
https://schema.org/PublicationVolume.comment:
A part of a successively published publication such as a periodical or multi-volume work, often numbered. It may represent a time span, such as a year.

See also blog post.

https://schema.org/Pulmonary.label: Pulmonary
https://schema.org/Pulmonary.comment: A specific branch of medical science that pertains to the study of the respiratory system and its respective disease states.

https://schema.org/QAPage.label: QAPage
https://schema.org/QAPage.comment: A QAPage is a WebPage focussed on a specific Question and its Answer(s), e.g. in a question answering site or documenting Frequently Asked Questions (FAQs).

https://schema.org/QualitativeValue.label: QualitativeValue
https://schema.org/QualitativeValue.comment: A predefined value for a product characteristic, e.g. the power cord plug type 'US' or the garment sizes 'S', 'M', 'L', and 'XL'.

https://schema.org/QuantitativeValue.label: QuantitativeValue
https://schema.org/QuantitativeValue.comment: A point value or interval for product characteristics and other purposes.

https://schema.org/Quantity.label: Quantity
https://schema.org/Quantity.comment: Quantities such as distance, time, mass, weight, etc. Particular instances of say Mass are entities like '3 kg' or '4 milligrams'.

https://schema.org/Question.label: Question
https://schema.org/Question.comment: A specific question - e.g. from a user seeking answers online, or collected in a Frequently Asked Questions (FAQ) document.

https://schema.org/Quiz.label: Quiz
https://schema.org/Quiz.comment: Quiz: A test of knowledge, skills and abilities.

https://schema.org/Quotation.label: Quotation
https://schema.org/Quotation.comment: A quotation. Often but not necessarily from some written work, attributable to a real world author and - if associated with a fictional character - to any fictional Person. Use isBasedOn to link to source/origin. The recordedIn property can be used to reference a Quotation from an Event.

https://schema.org/QuoteAction.label: QuoteAction
https://schema.org/QuoteAction.comment: An agent quotes/estimates/appraises an object/product/service with a price at a location/store.

https://schema.org/RVPark.label: RVPark
https://schema.org/RVPark.comment: A place offering space for "Recreational Vehicles", Caravans, mobile homes and the like.

https://schema.org/RadiationTherapy.label: RadiationTherapy
https://schema.org/RadiationTherapy.comment: A process of care using radiation aimed at improving a health condition.

https://schema.org/RadioBroadcastService.label: RadioBroadcastService
https://schema.org/RadioBroadcastService.comment: A delivery service through which radio content is provided via broadcast over the air or online.

https://schema.org/RadioChannel.label: RadioChannel
https://schema.org/RadioChannel.comment: A unique instance of a radio BroadcastService on a CableOrSatelliteService lineup.

https://schema.org/RadioClip.label: RadioClip
https://schema.org/RadioClip.comment: A short radio program or a segment/part of a radio program.

https://schema.org/RadioEpisode.label: RadioEpisode
https://schema.org/RadioEpisode.comment: A radio episode which can be part of a series or season.

https://schema.org/RadioSeason.label: RadioSeason
https://schema.org/RadioSeason.comment: Season dedicated to radio broadcast and associated online delivery.

https://schema.org/RadioSeries.label: RadioSeries
https://schema.org/RadioSeries.comment: CreativeWorkSeries dedicated to radio broadcast and associated online delivery.

https://schema.org/Radiography.label: Radiography
https://schema.org/Radiography.comment: Radiography is an imaging technique that uses electromagnetic radiation other than visible light, especially X-rays, to view the internal structure of a non-uniformly composed and opaque object such as the human body.

https://schema.org/Rating.label: Rating
https://schema.org/Rating.comment: A rating is an evaluation on a numeric scale, such as 1 to 5 stars.

https://schema.org/ReactAction.label: ReactAction
https://schema.org/ReactAction.comment: The act of responding instinctively and emotionally to an object, expressing a sentiment.

https://schema.org/ReadAction.label: ReadAction
https://schema.org/ReadAction.comment: The act of consuming written content.

https://schema.org/ReadPermission.label: ReadPermission
https://schema.org/ReadPermission.comment: Permission to read or view the document.

https://schema.org/RealEstateListing.label: RealEstateListing
https://schema.org/RealEstateListing.comment: A RealEstateListing is a listing that describes one or more real-estate Offers (whose businessFunction is typically to lease out, or to sell). The RealEstateListing type itself represents the overall listing, as manifested in some WebPage.

https://schema.org/RearWheelDriveConfigu.label: RearWheelDriveConfiguration
https://schema.org/RearWheelDriveConfigu.comment: Real-wheel drive is a transmission layout where the engine drives the rear wheels.

https://schema.org/ReceiveAction.label: ReceiveAction
https://schema.org/ReceiveAction.comment:
The act of physically/electronically taking delivery of an object that has been transferred from an origin to a destination. Reciprocal of SendAction.

Related actions:

  • SendAction: The reciprocal of ReceiveAction.
  • TakeAction: Unlike TakeAction, ReceiveAction does not imply that the ownership has been transferred (e.g. I can receive a package, but it does not mean the package is now mine).

https://schema.org/Recipe.label: Recipe
https://schema.org/Recipe.comment: A recipe. For dietary restrictions covered by the recipe, a few common restrictions are enumerated via suitableForDiet. The keywords property can also be used to add more detail.

https://schema.org/Recommendation.label: Recommendation
https://schema.org/Recommendation.comment: Recommendation is a type of Review that suggests or proposes something as the best option or best course of action. Recommendations may be for products or services, or other concrete things, as in the case of a ranked list or product guide. A Guide may list multiple recommendations for different categories. For example, in a Guide about which TVs to buy, the author may have several Recommendations.

https://schema.org/RecommendedDoseSchedu.label: RecommendedDoseSchedule
https://schema.org/RecommendedDoseSchedu.comment: A recommended dosing schedule for a drug or supplement as prescribed or recommended by an authority or by the drug/supplement's manufacturer. Capture the recommending authority in the recognizingAuthority property of MedicalEntity.

https://schema.org/ReducedRelevanceForCh.label: ReducedRelevanceForChildrenConsideration
https://schema.org/ReducedRelevanceForCh.comment: A general code for cases where relevance to children is reduced, e.g. adult education, mortgages, retirement-related products, etc.

https://schema.org/RefundTypeEnumeration.label: RefundTypeEnumeration
https://schema.org/RefundTypeEnumeration.comment: Enumerates several kinds of product return refund types.

https://schema.org/RefurbishedCondition.label: RefurbishedCondition
https://schema.org/RefurbishedCondition.comment: Indicates that the item is refurbished.

https://schema.org/RegisterAction.label: RegisterAction
https://schema.org/RegisterAction.comment:
The act of registering to be a user of a service, product or web page.

Related actions:

  • JoinAction: Unlike JoinAction, RegisterAction implies you are registering to be a user of a service, not a group/team of people.
  • FollowAction: Unlike FollowAction, RegisterAction doesn't imply that the agent is expecting to poll for updates from the object.
  • SubscribeAction: Unlike SubscribeAction, RegisterAction doesn't imply that the agent is expecting updates from the object.

https://schema.org/RegularPrice.label: RegularPrice
https://schema.org/RegularPrice.comment: Represents the regular price of an offered product. This is usually the advertised price before a temporary sale. Once the sale period ends the advertised price will go back to the regular price.

https://schema.org/ReimbursementCap.label: ReimbursementCap
https://schema.org/ReimbursementCap.comment: The drug's cost represents the maximum reimbursement paid by an insurer for the drug.

https://schema.org/RejectAction.label: RejectAction
https://schema.org/RejectAction.comment:
The act of rejecting to/adopting an object.

Related actions:

  • AcceptAction: The antonym of RejectAction.

https://schema.org/RelatedTopicsHealthAs.label: RelatedTopicsHealthAspect
https://schema.org/RelatedTopicsHealthAs.comment: Other prominent or relevant topics tied to the main topic.

https://schema.org/Renal.label: Renal
https://schema.org/Renal.comment: A specific branch of medical science that pertains to the study of the kidneys and its respective disease states.

https://schema.org/RentAction.label: RentAction
https://schema.org/RentAction.comment: The act of giving money in return for temporary use, but not ownership, of an object such as a vehicle or property. For example, an agent rents a property from a landlord in exchange for a periodic payment.

https://schema.org/RentalCarReservation.label: RentalCarReservation
https://schema.org/RentalCarReservation.comment:
A reservation for a rental car.

Note: This type is for information about actual reservations, e.g. in confirmation emails or HTML pages with individual confirmations of reservations.

https://schema.org/RentalVehicleUsage.label: RentalVehicleUsage
https://schema.org/RentalVehicleUsage.comment: Indicates the usage of the vehicle as a rental car.

https://schema.org/ReplaceAction.label: ReplaceAction
https://schema.org/ReplaceAction.comment: The act of editing a recipient by replacing an old object with a new object.

https://schema.org/ReplyAction.label: ReplyAction
https://schema.org/ReplyAction.comment:
The act of responding to a question/message asked/sent by the object. Related to AskAction.

Related actions:

  • AskAction: Appears generally as an origin of a ReplyAction.

https://schema.org/Report.label: Report
https://schema.org/Report.comment: A Report generated by governmental or non-governmental organization.

https://schema.org/ReportageNewsArticle.label: ReportageNewsArticle
https://schema.org/ReportageNewsArticle.comment:
The ReportageNewsArticle type is a subtype of NewsArticle representing news articles which are the result of journalistic news reporting conventions.

In practice many news publishers produce a wide variety of article types, many of which might be considered a NewsArticle but not a ReportageNewsArticle. For example, opinion pieces, reviews, analysis, sponsored or satirical articles, or articles that combine several of these elements.

The ReportageNewsArticle type is based on a stricter ideal for "news" as a work of journalism, with articles based on factual information either observed or verified by the author, or reported and verified from knowledgeable sources. This often includes perspectives from multiple viewpoints on a particular issue (distinguishing news reports from public relations or propaganda). News reports in the ReportageNewsArticle sense de-emphasize the opinion of the author, with commentary and value judgements typically expressed elsewhere.

A ReportageNewsArticle which goes deeper into analysis can also be marked with an additional type of AnalysisNewsArticle.

https://schema.org/ReportedDoseSchedule.label: ReportedDoseSchedule
https://schema.org/ReportedDoseSchedule.comment: A patient-reported or observed dosing schedule for a drug or supplement.

https://schema.org/ResearchOrganization.label: ResearchOrganization
https://schema.org/ResearchOrganization.comment: A Research Organization (e.g. scientific institute, research company).

https://schema.org/Reservation.label: Reservation
https://schema.org/Reservation.comment:
Describes a reservation for travel, dining or an event. Some reservations require tickets.

Note: This type is for information about actual reservations, e.g. in confirmation emails or HTML pages with individual confirmations of reservations. For offers of tickets, restaurant reservations, flights, or rental cars, use Offer.

https://schema.org/ReservationCancelled.label: ReservationCancelled
https://schema.org/ReservationCancelled.comment: The status for a previously confirmed reservation that is now cancelled.

https://schema.org/ReservationConfirmed.label: ReservationConfirmed
https://schema.org/ReservationConfirmed.comment: The status of a confirmed reservation.

https://schema.org/ReservationHold.label: ReservationHold
https://schema.org/ReservationHold.comment: The status of a reservation on hold pending an update like credit card number or flight changes.

https://schema.org/ReservationPackage.label: ReservationPackage
https://schema.org/ReservationPackage.comment: A group of multiple reservations with common values for all sub-reservations.

https://schema.org/ReservationPending.label: ReservationPending
https://schema.org/ReservationPending.comment: The status of a reservation when a request has been sent, but not confirmed.

https://schema.org/ReserveAction.label: ReserveAction
https://schema.org/ReserveAction.comment:
Reserving a concrete object.

Related actions:

  • ScheduleAction: Unlike ScheduleAction, ReserveAction reserves concrete objects (e.g. a table, a hotel) towards a time slot / spatial allocation.

https://schema.org/Reserved.label: Reserved
https://schema.org/Reserved.comment: Indicates that the item is reserved and therefore not available.

https://schema.org/Reservoir.label: Reservoir
https://schema.org/Reservoir.comment: A reservoir of water, typically an artificially created lake, like the Lake Kariba reservoir.

https://schema.org/Residence.label: Residence
https://schema.org/Residence.comment: The place where a person lives.

https://schema.org/Resort.label: Resort
https://schema.org/Resort.comment:
A resort is a place used for relaxation or recreation, attracting visitors for holidays or vacations. Resorts are places, towns or sometimes commercial establishments operated by a single company (source: Wikipedia, the free encyclopedia, see http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Resort).

See also the dedicated document on the use of schema.org for marking up hotels and other forms of accommodations.

https://schema.org/RespiratoryTherapy.label: RespiratoryTherapy
https://schema.org/RespiratoryTherapy.comment: The therapy that is concerned with the maintenance or improvement of respiratory function (as in patients with pulmonary disease).

https://schema.org/RestockingFees.label: RestockingFees
https://schema.org/RestockingFees.comment: Specifies that the customer must pay a restocking fee when returning a product.

https://schema.org/RestrictedDiet.label: RestrictedDiet
https://schema.org/RestrictedDiet.comment: A diet restricted to certain foods or preparations for cultural, religious, health or lifestyle reasons.

https://schema.org/ResumeAction.label: ResumeAction
https://schema.org/ResumeAction.comment: The act of resuming a device or application which was formerly paused (e.g. resume music playback or resume a timer).

https://schema.org/Retail.label: Retail
https://schema.org/Retail.comment: The drug's cost represents the retail cost of the drug.

https://schema.org/ReturnAction.label: ReturnAction
https://schema.org/ReturnAction.comment: The act of returning to the origin that which was previously received (concrete objects) or taken (ownership).

https://schema.org/ReturnAtKiosk.label: ReturnAtKiosk
https://schema.org/ReturnAtKiosk.comment: Specifies that product returns must be made at a kiosk.

https://schema.org/ReturnByMail.label: ReturnByMail
https://schema.org/ReturnByMail.comment: Specifies that product returns must be done by mail.

https://schema.org/ReturnFeesCustomerRes.label: ReturnFeesCustomerResponsibility
https://schema.org/ReturnFeesCustomerRes.comment: Specifies that product returns must be paid for, and are the responsibility of, the customer.

https://schema.org/ReturnFeesEnumeration.label: ReturnFeesEnumeration
https://schema.org/ReturnFeesEnumeration.comment: Enumerates several kinds of policies for product return fees.

https://schema.org/ReturnInStore.label: ReturnInStore
https://schema.org/ReturnInStore.comment: Specifies that product returns must be made in a store.

https://schema.org/ReturnLabelCustomerRe.label: ReturnLabelCustomerResponsibility
https://schema.org/ReturnLabelCustomerRe.comment: Indicated that creating a return label is the responsibility of the customer.

https://schema.org/ReturnLabelDownloadAn.label: ReturnLabelDownloadAndPrint
https://schema.org/ReturnLabelDownloadAn.comment: Indicated that a return label must be downloaded and printed by the customer.

https://schema.org/ReturnLabelInBox.label: ReturnLabelInBox
https://schema.org/ReturnLabelInBox.comment: Specifies that a return label will be provided by the seller in the shipping box.

https://schema.org/ReturnLabelSourceEnum.label: ReturnLabelSourceEnumeration
https://schema.org/ReturnLabelSourceEnum.comment: Enumerates several types of return labels for product returns.

https://schema.org/ReturnMethodEnumerati.label: ReturnMethodEnumeration
https://schema.org/ReturnMethodEnumerati.comment: Enumerates several types of product return methods.

https://schema.org/ReturnShippingFees.label: ReturnShippingFees
https://schema.org/ReturnShippingFees.comment: Specifies that the customer must pay the return shipping costs when returning a product.

https://schema.org/Review.label: Review
https://schema.org/Review.comment: A review of an item - for example, of a restaurant, movie, or store.

https://schema.org/ReviewAction.label: ReviewAction
https://schema.org/ReviewAction.comment: The act of producing a balanced opinion about the object for an audience. An agent reviews an object with participants resulting in a review.

https://schema.org/ReviewNewsArticle.label: ReviewNewsArticle
https://schema.org/ReviewNewsArticle.comment: A NewsArticle and CriticReview providing a professional critic's assessment of a service, product, performance, or artistic or literary work.

https://schema.org/Rheumatologic.label: Rheumatologic
https://schema.org/Rheumatologic.comment: A specific branch of medical science that deals with the study and treatment of rheumatic, autoimmune or joint diseases.

https://schema.org/RightHandDriving.label: RightHandDriving
https://schema.org/RightHandDriving.comment: The steering position is on the right side of the vehicle (viewed from the main direction of driving).

https://schema.org/RisksOrComplicationsH.label: RisksOrComplicationsHealthAspect
https://schema.org/RisksOrComplicationsH.comment: Information about the risk factors and possible complications that may follow a topic.

https://schema.org/RiverBodyOfWater.label: RiverBodyOfWater
https://schema.org/RiverBodyOfWater.comment: A river (for example, the broad majestic Shannon).

https://schema.org/Role.label: Role
https://schema.org/Role.comment:
Represents additional information about a relationship or property. For example a Role can be used to say that a 'member' role linking some SportsTeam to a player occurred during a particular time period. Or that a Person's 'actor' role in a Movie was for some particular characterName. Such properties can be attached to a Role entity, which is then associated with the main entities using ordinary properties like 'member' or 'actor'.

See also blog post.

https://schema.org/Room.label: Room
https://schema.org/Room.comment:
A room is a distinguishable space within a structure, usually separated from other spaces by interior walls (source: Wikipedia, the free encyclopedia, see http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Room).

See also the dedicated document on the use of schema.org for marking up hotels and other forms of accommodations.

https://schema.org/RsvpAction.label: RsvpAction
https://schema.org/RsvpAction.comment: The act of notifying an event organizer as to whether you expect to attend the event.

https://schema.org/RsvpResponseMaybe.label: RsvpResponseMaybe
https://schema.org/RsvpResponseMaybe.comment: The invitee may or may not attend.

https://schema.org/RsvpResponseType.label: RsvpResponseType
https://schema.org/RsvpResponseType.comment: RsvpResponseType is an enumeration type whose instances represent responding to an RSVP request.

https://schema.org/SRP.label: SRP
https://schema.org/SRP.comment: Represents the suggested retail price ("SRP") of an offered product.

https://schema.org/SafetyHealthAspect.label: SafetyHealthAspect
https://schema.org/SafetyHealthAspect.comment: Content about the safety-related aspects of a health topic.

https://schema.org/SalePrice.label: SalePrice
https://schema.org/SalePrice.comment: Represents a sale price (usually active for a limited period) of an offered product.

https://schema.org/SatireOrParodyContent.label: SatireOrParodyContent
https://schema.org/SatireOrParodyContent.comment:
Content coded 'satire or parody content' in a MediaReview, considered in the context of how it was published or shared.

For a VideoObject to be 'satire or parody content': A video that was created as political or humorous commentary and is presented in that context. (Reshares of satire/parody content that do not include relevant context are more likely to fall under the missing context rating.)

For an ImageObject to be 'satire or parody content': An image that was created as political or humorous commentary and is presented in that context. (Reshares of satire/parody content that do not include relevant context are more likely to fall under the missing context rating.)

For an ImageObject with embedded text to be 'satire or parody content': An image that was created as political or humorous commentary and is presented in that context. (Reshares of satire/parody content that do not include relevant context are more likely to fall under the missing context rating.)

For an AudioObject to be 'satire or parody content': Audio that was created as political or humorous commentary and is presented in that context. (Reshares of satire/parody content that do not include relevant context are more likely to fall under the missing context rating.)

https://schema.org/SatiricalArticle.label: SatiricalArticle
https://schema.org/SatiricalArticle.comment: An Article whose content is primarily [satirical] in nature, i.e. unlikely to be literally true. A satirical article is sometimes but not necessarily also a NewsArticle. ScholarlyArticles are also sometimes satirized.

https://schema.org/Saturday.label: Saturday
https://schema.org/Saturday.comment: The day of the week between Friday and Sunday.

https://schema.org/Schedule.label: Schedule
https://schema.org/Schedule.comment: A schedule defines a repeating time period used to describe a regularly occurring Event. At a minimum a schedule will specify repeatFrequency which describes the interval between occurrences of the event. Additional information can be provided to specify the schedule more precisely. This includes identifying the day(s) of the week or month when the recurring event will take place, in addition to its start and end time. Schedules may also have start and end dates to indicate when they are active, e.g. to define a limited calendar of events.

https://schema.org/ScheduleAction.label: ScheduleAction
https://schema.org/ScheduleAction.comment:
Scheduling future actions, events, or tasks.

Related actions:

  • ReserveAction: Unlike ReserveAction, ScheduleAction allocates future actions (e.g. an event, a task, etc) towards a time slot / spatial allocation.

https://schema.org/SchoolDistrict.label: SchoolDistrict
https://schema.org/SchoolDistrict.comment: A School District is an administrative area for the administration of schools.

https://schema.org/ScreenCaptureDigitalS.label: ScreenCaptureDigitalSource
https://schema.org/ScreenCaptureDigitalS.comment: Content coded as 'algorithmic media' using the IPTC digital source type vocabulary.

https://schema.org/ScreeningEvent.label: ScreeningEvent
https://schema.org/ScreeningEvent.comment: A screening of a movie or other video.

https://schema.org/ScreeningHealthAspect.label: ScreeningHealthAspect
https://schema.org/ScreeningHealthAspect.comment: Content about how to screen or further filter a topic.

https://schema.org/SeaBodyOfWater.label: SeaBodyOfWater
https://schema.org/SeaBodyOfWater.comment: A sea (for example, the Caspian sea).

https://schema.org/SearchAction.label: SearchAction
https://schema.org/SearchAction.comment:
The act of searching for an object.

Related actions:

  • FindAction: SearchAction generally leads to a FindAction, but not necessarily.

https://schema.org/SearchRescueOrganizat.label: SearchRescueOrganization
https://schema.org/SearchRescueOrganizat.comment: A Search and Rescue organization of some kind.

https://schema.org/SearchResultsPage.label: SearchResultsPage
https://schema.org/SearchResultsPage.comment: Web page type: Search results page.

https://schema.org/Season.label: Season
https://schema.org/Season.comment: A media season, e.g. TV, radio, video game etc.

https://schema.org/Seat.label: Seat
https://schema.org/Seat.comment: Used to describe a seat, such as a reserved seat in an event reservation.

https://schema.org/SeeDoctorHealthAspect.label: SeeDoctorHealthAspect
https://schema.org/SeeDoctorHealthAspect.comment: Information about questions that may be asked, when to see a professional, measures before seeing a doctor or content about the first consultation.

https://schema.org/SeekToAction.label: SeekToAction
https://schema.org/SeekToAction.comment: This is the Action of navigating to a specific startOffset timestamp within a VideoObject, typically represented with a URL template structure.

https://schema.org/SelfCareHealthAspect.label: SelfCareHealthAspect
https://schema.org/SelfCareHealthAspect.comment: Self care actions or measures that can be taken to sooth, health or avoid a topic. This may be carried at home and can be carried/managed by the person itself.

https://schema.org/SellAction.label: SellAction
https://schema.org/SellAction.comment: The act of taking money from a buyer in exchange for goods or services rendered. An agent sells an object, product, or service to a buyer for a price. Reciprocal of BuyAction.

https://schema.org/SendAction.label: SendAction
https://schema.org/SendAction.comment:
The act of physically/electronically dispatching an object for transfer from an origin to a destination. Related actions:

  • ReceiveAction: The reciprocal of SendAction.
  • GiveAction: Unlike GiveAction, SendAction does not imply the transfer of ownership (e.g. I can send you my laptop, but I'm not necessarily giving it to you).

https://schema.org/Series.label: Series
https://schema.org/Series.comment: A Series in schema.org is a group of related items, typically but not necessarily of the same kind. See also CreativeWorkSeries, EventSeries.

https://schema.org/Service.label: Service
https://schema.org/Service.comment: A service provided by an organization, e.g. delivery service, print services, etc.

https://schema.org/ServiceChannel.label: ServiceChannel
https://schema.org/ServiceChannel.comment: A means for accessing a service, e.g. a government office location, web site, or phone number.

https://schema.org/SexualContentConsider.label: SexualContentConsideration
https://schema.org/SexualContentConsider.comment: The item contains sexually oriented content such as nudity, suggestive or explicit material, or related online services, or is intended to enhance sexual activity. Examples: Erotic videos or magazine, sexual enhancement devices, sex toys.

https://schema.org/ShareAction.label: ShareAction
https://schema.org/ShareAction.comment: The act of distributing content to people for their amusement or edification.

https://schema.org/SheetMusic.label: SheetMusic
https://schema.org/SheetMusic.comment: Printed music, as opposed to performed or recorded music.

https://schema.org/ShippingDeliveryTime.label: ShippingDeliveryTime
https://schema.org/ShippingDeliveryTime.comment: ShippingDeliveryTime provides various pieces of information about delivery times for shipping.

https://schema.org/ShippingRateSettings.label: ShippingRateSettings
https://schema.org/ShippingRateSettings.comment: A ShippingRateSettings represents re-usable pieces of shipping information. It is designed for publication on an URL that may be referenced via the shippingSettingsLink property of an OfferShippingDetails. Several occurrences can be published, distinguished and matched (i.e. identified/referenced) by their different values for shippingLabel.

https://schema.org/ShortStory.label: ShortStory
https://schema.org/ShortStory.comment: Short story or tale. A brief work of literature, usually written in narrative prose.

https://schema.org/SideEffectsHealthAspe.label: SideEffectsHealthAspect
https://schema.org/SideEffectsHealthAspe.comment: Side effects that can be observed from the usage of the topic.

https://schema.org/SingleBlindedTrial.label: SingleBlindedTrial
https://schema.org/SingleBlindedTrial.comment: A trial design in which the researcher knows which treatment the patient was randomly assigned to but the patient does not.

https://schema.org/SingleCenterTrial.label: SingleCenterTrial
https://schema.org/SingleCenterTrial.comment: A trial that takes place at a single center.

https://schema.org/SinglePlayer.label: SinglePlayer
https://schema.org/SinglePlayer.comment: Play mode: SinglePlayer. Which is played by a lone player.

https://schema.org/SiteNavigationElement.label: SiteNavigationElement
https://schema.org/SiteNavigationElement.comment: A navigation element of the page.

https://schema.org/SizeGroupEnumeration.label: SizeGroupEnumeration
https://schema.org/SizeGroupEnumeration.comment: Enumerates common size groups for various product categories.

https://schema.org/SizeSpecification.label: SizeSpecification
https://schema.org/SizeSpecification.comment: Size related properties of a product, typically a size code (name) and optionally a sizeSystem, sizeGroup, and product measurements (hasMeasurement). In addition, the intended audience can be defined through suggestedAge, suggestedGender, and suggested body measurements (suggestedMeasurement).

https://schema.org/SizeSystemEnumeration.label: SizeSystemEnumeration
https://schema.org/SizeSystemEnumeration.comment: Enumerates common size systems for different categories of products, for example "EN-13402" or "UK" for wearables or "Imperial" for screws.

https://schema.org/SocialMediaPosting.label: SocialMediaPosting
https://schema.org/SocialMediaPosting.comment: A post to a social media platform, including blog posts, tweets, Facebook posts, etc.

https://schema.org/SoftwareSourceCode.label: SoftwareSourceCode
https://schema.org/SoftwareSourceCode.comment: Computer programming source code. Example: Full (compile ready) solutions, code snippet samples, scripts, templates.

https://schema.org/SoldOut.label: SoldOut
https://schema.org/SoldOut.comment: Indicates that the item has sold out.

https://schema.org/SolveMathAction.label: SolveMathAction
https://schema.org/SolveMathAction.comment: The action that takes in a math expression and directs users to a page potentially capable of solving/simplifying that expression.

https://schema.org/SomeProducts.label: SomeProducts
https://schema.org/SomeProducts.comment: A placeholder for multiple similar products of the same kind.

https://schema.org/SpeakableSpecificatio.label: SpeakableSpecification
https://schema.org/SpeakableSpecificatio.comment: A SpeakableSpecification indicates (typically via xpath or cssSelector) sections of a document that are highlighted as particularly speakable. Instances of this type are expected to be used primarily as values of the speakable property.

https://schema.org/SpecialAnnouncement.label: SpecialAnnouncement
https://schema.org/SpecialAnnouncement.comment:
A SpecialAnnouncement combines a simple date-stamped textual information update with contextualized Web links and other structured data. It represents an information update made by a locally-oriented organization, for example schools, pharmacies, healthcare providers, community groups, police, local government.

For work in progress guidelines on Coronavirus-related markup see this doc.

The motivating scenario for SpecialAnnouncement is the Coronavirus pandemic, and the initial vocabulary is oriented to this urgent situation. Schema.org expect to improve the markup iteratively as it is deployed and as feedback emerges from use. In addition to our usual Github entry, feedback comments can also be provided in this document.

While this schema is designed to communicate urgent crisis-related information, it is not the same as an emergency warning technology like CAP, although there may be overlaps. The intent is to cover the kinds of everyday practical information being posted to existing websites during an emergency situation.

Several kinds of information can be provided:

We encourage the provision of "name", "text", "datePosted", "expires" (if appropriate), "category" and "url" as a simple baseline. It is important to provide a value for "category" where possible, most ideally as a well known URL from Wikipedia or Wikidata. In the case of the 2019-2020 Coronavirus pandemic, this should be "https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=2019-20_coronavirus_pandemic" or "https://www.wikidata.org/wiki/Q81068910".

For many of the possible properties, values can either be simple links or an inline description, depending on whether a summary is available. For a link, provide just the URL of the appropriate page as the property's value. For an inline description, use a WebContent type, and provide the url as a property of that, alongside at least a simple "text" summary of the page. It is unlikely that a single SpecialAnnouncement will need all of the possible properties simultaneously.

We expect that in many cases the page referenced might contain more specialized structured data, e.g. contact info, openingHours, Event, FAQPage etc. By linking to those pages from a SpecialAnnouncement you can help make it clearer that the events are related to the situation (e.g. Coronavirus) indicated by the category property of the SpecialAnnouncement.

Many SpecialAnnouncements will relate to particular regions and to identifiable local organizations. Use spatialCoverage for the region, and announcementLocation to indicate specific LocalBusinesses and CivicStructures. If the announcement affects both a particular region and a specific location (for example, a library closure that serves an entire region), use both spatialCoverage and announcementLocation.

The about property can be used to indicate entities that are the focus of the announcement. We now recommend using about only for representing non-location entities (e.g. a Course or a RadioStation). For places, use announcementLocation and spatialCoverage. Consumers of this markup should be aware that the initial design encouraged the use of about for locations too.

The basic content of SpecialAnnouncement is similar to that of an RSS or Atom feed. For publishers without such feeds, basic feed-like information can be shared by posting SpecialAnnouncement updates in a page, e.g. using JSON-LD. For sites with Atom/RSS functionality, you can point to a feed with the webFeed property. This can be a simple URL, or an inline DataFeed object, with encodingFormat providing media type information, e.g. "application/rss+xml" or "application/atom+xml".

https://schema.org/Specialty.label: Specialty
https://schema.org/Specialty.comment: Any branch of a field in which people typically develop specific expertise, usually after significant study, time, and effort.

https://schema.org/SpeechPathology.label: SpeechPathology
https://schema.org/SpeechPathology.comment: The scientific study and treatment of defects, disorders, and malfunctions of speech and voice, as stuttering, lisping, or lalling, and of language disturbances, as aphasia or delayed language acquisition.

https://schema.org/SportsActivityLocatio.label: SportsActivityLocation
https://schema.org/SportsActivityLocatio.comment: A sports location, such as a playing field.

https://schema.org/SportsOrganization.label: SportsOrganization
https://schema.org/SportsOrganization.comment: Represents the collection of all sports organizations, including sports teams, governing bodies, and sports associations.

https://schema.org/StagedContent.label: StagedContent
https://schema.org/StagedContent.comment:
Content coded 'staged content' in a MediaReview, considered in the context of how it was published or shared.

For a VideoObject to be 'staged content': A video that has been created using actors or similarly contrived.

For an ImageObject to be 'staged content': An image that was created using actors or similarly contrived, such as a screenshot of a fake tweet.

For an ImageObject with embedded text to be 'staged content': An image that was created using actors or similarly contrived, such as a screenshot of a fake tweet.

For an AudioObject to be 'staged content': Audio that has been created using actors or similarly contrived.

https://schema.org/StagesHealthAspect.label: StagesHealthAspect
https://schema.org/StagesHealthAspect.comment: Stages that can be observed from a topic.

https://schema.org/State.label: State
https://schema.org/State.comment: A state or province of a country.

https://schema.org/Statement.label: Statement
https://schema.org/Statement.comment: A statement about something, for example a fun or interesting fact. If known, the main entity this statement is about can be indicated using mainEntity. For more formal claims (e.g. in Fact Checking), consider using Claim instead. Use the text property to capture the text of the statement.

https://schema.org/StatisticalPopulation.label: StatisticalPopulation
https://schema.org/StatisticalPopulation.comment: A StatisticalPopulation is a set of instances of a certain given type that satisfy some set of constraints. The property populationType is used to specify the type. Any property that can be used on instances of that type can appear on the statistical population. For example, a StatisticalPopulation representing all Persons with a homeLocation of East Podunk California would be described by applying the appropriate homeLocation and populationType properties to a StatisticalPopulation item that stands for that set of people. The properties numConstraints and constraintProperty are used to specify which of the populations properties are used to specify the population. Note that the sense of "population" used here is the general sense of a statistical population, and does not imply that the population consists of people. For example, a populationType of Event or NewsArticle could be used. See also Observation, where a populationType such as Person or Event can be indicated directly. In most cases it may be better to use StatisticalVariable instead of StatisticalPopulation.

https://schema.org/StatisticalVariable.label: StatisticalVariable
https://schema.org/StatisticalVariable.comment: StatisticalVariable represents any type of statistical metric that can be measured at a place and time. The usage pattern for StatisticalVariable is typically expressed using Observation with an explicit populationType, which is a type, typically drawn from Schema.org. Each StatisticalVariable is marked as a ConstraintNode, meaning that some properties (those listed using constraintProperty) serve in this setting solely to define the statistical variable rather than literally describe a specific person, place or thing. For example, a StatisticalVariable MedianHeightPerson_Female representing the median height of women, could be written as follows: the population type is Person; the measuredProperty height; the statType median; the gender Female.
